# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: discrete-mathematics
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:discrete-mathematics/binary-relation-p01] In mathematics, a **binary relation** associates some elements of one set called the *domain* with some elements of another set (possibly the same) called the *codomain*.
[src:discrete-mathematics/binary-relation-p01] A binary relation is called a homogeneous relation when X = Y {\displaystyle X=Y} ({\displaystyle X=Y}).
[src:discrete-mathematics/binary-relation-p01] A binary relation is also called a *heterogeneous relation* when it is not necessary that X = Y {\displaystyle X=Y} ({\displaystyle X=Y}).
[src:discrete-mathematics/binary-relation-p01] Binary relations, and especially homogeneous relations, are used in many branches of mathematics to model a wide variety of concepts.
[src:discrete-mathematics/binary-relation-p01] A function may be defined as a binary relation that meets additional constraints.
[src:discrete-mathematics/binary-relation-p01] Binary relations are also heavily used in computer science.
[src:discrete-mathematics/binary-relation-p01] In some systems of axiomatic set theory, relations are extended to classes, which are generalizations of sets.
[src:discrete-mathematics/binary-relation-p01] This extension is needed for, among other things, modeling the concepts of "is an element of" or "is a subset of" in set theory, without running into logical inconsistencies such as Russell's paradox.
[src:discrete-mathematics/binary-relation-p01] The statement ( x , y ) ∈ R {\displaystyle (x,y)\in R} ({\displaystyle (x,y)\in R}) reads " x {\displaystyle x} ({\displaystyle x}) is R {\displaystyle R} ({\displaystyle R})-related to y {\displaystyle y} ({\displaystyle y})" and is denoted by x R y {\displaystyle xRy} ({\displaystyle xRy}).
[src:discrete-mathematics/binary-relation-p01] The *domain of definition* or *active domain* of R {\displaystyle R} ({\displaystyle R}) is the set of all x {\displaystyle x} ({\displaystyle x}) such that x R y {\displaystyle xRy} ({\displaystyle xRy}) for at least one y {\displaystyle y} ({\displaystyle y}).
[src:discrete-mathematics/binary-relation-p01] The *codomain of definition*, *active codomain*, *image* or *range* of R {\displaystyle R} ({\displaystyle R}) is the set of all y {\displaystyle y} ({\displaystyle y}) such that x R y {\displaystyle xRy} ({\displaystyle xRy}) for at least one x {\displaystyle x} ({\displaystyle x}).
[src:discrete-mathematics/binary-relation-p01] The *field* of R {\displaystyle R} ({\displaystyle R}) is the union of its domain of definition and its codomain of definition.
[src:discrete-mathematics/binary-relation-p01] When X = Y , {\displaystyle X=Y,} ({\displaystyle X=Y,}) a binary relation is called a *homogeneous relation* (or *endorelation*).
[src:discrete-mathematics/binary-relation-p01] To emphasize the fact that X {\displaystyle X} ({\displaystyle X}) and Y {\displaystyle Y} ({\displaystyle Y}) are allowed to be different, a binary relation is also called a **heterogeneous relation**.
[src:discrete-mathematics/binary-relation-p01] The prefix *hetero* is from the Greek ἕτερος (*heteros*, "other, another, different").
[src:discrete-mathematics/binary-relation-p01] In a binary relation, the order of the elements is important; if x ≠ y {\displaystyle x\neq y} ({\displaystyle x\neq y}) then y R x {\displaystyle yRx} ({\displaystyle yRx}) can be true or false independently of x R y {\displaystyle xRy} ({\displaystyle xRy}).
[src:discrete-mathematics/binary-relation-p01] For example, 3 {\displaystyle 3} ({\displaystyle 3}) divides 9 {\displaystyle 9} ({\displaystyle 9}), but 9 {\displaystyle 9} ({\displaystyle 9}) does not divide 3 {\displaystyle 3} ({\displaystyle 3}).
[src:discrete-mathematics/binary-relation-p01] The identity element is the empty relation, in which no x {\displaystyle x} ({\displaystyle x}) is related to any y {\displaystyle y} ({\displaystyle y}).
[src:discrete-mathematics/binary-relation-p01] The identity element is the universal relation, in which every x {\displaystyle x} ({\displaystyle x}) is related to every y {\displaystyle y} ({\displaystyle y}).
[src:discrete-mathematics/binary-relation-p01] For example, the relation "is divisible by 6" is the intersection of the relations "is divisible by 3" and "is divisible by 2".
[src:discrete-mathematics/binary-relation-p01] If X = Y = Z {\displaystyle X=Y=Z} ({\displaystyle X=Y=Z}), the identity element w.r.t. composition is the identity relation on X {\displaystyle X} ({\displaystyle X}), in which x ∈ X {\displaystyle x\in X} ({\displaystyle x\in X}) is related only to itself.
[src:discrete-mathematics/binary-relation-p01] The order of R {\displaystyle R} ({\displaystyle R}) and S {\displaystyle S} ({\displaystyle S}) in the notation S ∘ R {\displaystyle S\circ R} ({\displaystyle S\circ R}) used here agrees with the standard notational order for composition of functions.
[src:discrete-mathematics/binary-relation-p01] For example, the composition (is parent of) ∘ {\displaystyle \circ } ({\displaystyle \circ })(is mother of) yields (is grandmother of), while the composition (is mother of) ∘ {\displaystyle \circ } ({\displaystyle \circ })(is parent of) yields (is maternal grandparent of).
[src:discrete-mathematics/binary-relation-p01] If a relation is reflexive, irreflexive, symmetric, antisymmetric, asymmetric, transitive, total, trichotomous, a partial order, total order, strict weak order, total preorder (weak order), or an equivalence relation, then so too are its restrictions.
[src:discrete-mathematics/binary-relation-p01] However, the transitive closure of a restriction is a subset of the restriction of the transitive closure, i.e., in general not equal.
[src:discrete-mathematics/binary-relation-p01] On the other hand, the transitive closure of "is parent of" is "is ancestor of"; its restriction to females does relate a woman with her paternal grandmother.
[src:discrete-mathematics/binary-relation-p01] Also, the various concepts of completeness (not to be confused with being "total") do not carry over to restrictions.
[src:discrete-mathematics/binary-relation-p01] Homogeneous relations (when X = Y {\displaystyle X=Y} ({\displaystyle X=Y})) form a matrix semiring (indeed, a matrix semialgebra over the Boolean semiring) where the identity matrix corresponds to the identity relation.
[src:discrete-mathematics/binary-relation-p01] Let a R b {\displaystyle aRb} ({\displaystyle aRb}) represent that ocean a {\displaystyle a} ({\displaystyle a}) borders continent b {\displaystyle b} ({\displaystyle b}).
[src:discrete-mathematics/binary-relation-p01] This universal relation reflects the fact that every ocean is separated from the others by at most one continent.
[src:discrete-mathematics/binary-relation-p01] On the other hand, R T R {\displaystyle R^{\mathsf {T}}R} ({\displaystyle R^{\mathsf {T}}R}) is a relation on B × B {\displaystyle B\times B} ({\displaystyle B\times B}) which *fails* to be universal because at least two oceans must be traversed to voyage from Europe to Australia.
[src:discrete-mathematics/binary-relation-p01] Visualization of relations leans on graph theory: For relations on a set (homogeneous relations), a directed graph illustrates a relation and a graph a symmetric relation.
[src:discrete-mathematics/binary-relation-p01] For heterogeneous relations a hypergraph has edges possibly with more than two nodes, and can be illustrated by a bipartite graph.
[src:discrete-mathematics/binary-relation-p01] Just as the clique is integral to relations on a set, so bicliques are used to describe heterogeneous relations; indeed, they are the "concepts" that generate a lattice associated with a relation.
[src:discrete-mathematics/binary-relation-p01] Hyperbolic orthogonality: Time and space are different categories, and temporal properties are separate from spatial properties.
[src:discrete-mathematics/binary-relation-p01] The idea of *simultaneous events* is simple in absolute space and time since each time t {\displaystyle t} ({\displaystyle t}) determines a simultaneous hyperplane in that cosmology.
[src:discrete-mathematics/binary-relation-p01] Hermann Minkowski changed that when he articulated the notion of *relative simultaneity*, which exists when spatial events are "normal" to a time characterized by a velocity.
[src:discrete-mathematics/binary-relation-p01] He used an indefinite inner product, and specified that a time vector is normal to a space vector when that product is zero.
[src:discrete-mathematics/binary-relation-p01] The indefinite inner product in a composition algebra is given by ⟨ x , z ⟩ = x z ¯ + x ¯ z {\displaystyle \langle x,z\rangle =x{\bar {z}}+{\bar {x}}z\;} ({\displaystyle \langle x,z\rangle =x{\bar {z}}+{\bar {x}}z\;}) where the overbar denotes conjugation.
[src:discrete-mathematics/binary-relation-p01] As a relation between some temporal events and some spatial events, hyperbolic orthogonality (as found in split-complex numbers) is a heterogeneous relation.
[src:discrete-mathematics/binary-relation-p01] A geometric configuration can be considered a relation between its points and its lines.
[src:discrete-mathematics/binary-relation-p01] Finite and infinite projective and affine planes are included.
[src:discrete-mathematics/binary-relation-p01] These incidence structures have been generalized with block designs.
[src:discrete-mathematics/binary-relation-p01] The incidence matrix used in these geometrical contexts corresponds to the logical matrix used generally with binary relations.
[src:discrete-mathematics/binary-relation-p01] Some important types of binary relations R {\displaystyle R} ({\displaystyle R}) over sets X {\displaystyle X} ({\displaystyle X}) and Y {\displaystyle Y} ({\displaystyle Y}) are listed below.
[src:discrete-mathematics/binary-relation-p01] Certain mathematical "relations", such as "equal to", "subset of", and "member of", cannot be understood to be binary relations as defined above, because their domains and codomains cannot be taken to be sets in the usual systems of axiomatic set theory.
[src:discrete-mathematics/binary-relation-p01] For example, to model the general concept of "equality" as a binary relation = {\displaystyle =} ({\displaystyle =}), take the domain and codomain to be the "class of all sets", which is not a set in the usual set theory.
[src:discrete-mathematics/binary-relation-p01] In most mathematical contexts, references to the relations of equality, membership and subset are harmless because they can be understood implicitly to be restricted to some set in the context.
[src:discrete-mathematics/binary-relation-p01] The usual work-around to this problem is to select a "large enough" set A {\displaystyle A} ({\displaystyle A}), that contains all the objects of interest, and work with the restriction = A {\displaystyle =_{A}} ({\displaystyle =_{A}}) instead of = {\displaystyle =} ({\displaystyle =}).
[src:discrete-mathematics/binary-relation-p01] Bertrand Russell has shown that assuming ∈ {\displaystyle \in } ({\displaystyle \in }) to be defined over all sets leads to a contradiction in naive set theory, see *Russell's paradox*.
[src:discrete-mathematics/binary-relation-p01] Another solution to this problem is to use a set theory with proper classes, such as NBG or Morse–Kelley set theory, and allow the domain and codomain (and so the graph) to be proper classes: in such a theory, equality, membership, and subset are binary relations without special comment.
[src:discrete-mathematics/binary-relation-p01] Considering composition of relations as a binary operation on B ( X ) {\displaystyle {\mathcal {B}}(X)} ({\displaystyle {\mathcal {B}}(X)}), it forms a semigroup with involution.
[src:discrete-mathematics/binary-relation-p01] A *partial order* is a relation that is reflexive, antisymmetric, and transitive.
[src:discrete-mathematics/binary-relation-p01] A *strict partial order* is a relation that is irreflexive, asymmetric, and transitive.
[src:discrete-mathematics/binary-relation-p01] A *total order* is a relation that is reflexive, antisymmetric, transitive and connected.
[src:discrete-mathematics/binary-relation-p01] A *strict total order* is a relation that is irreflexive, asymmetric, transitive and connected.
[src:discrete-mathematics/binary-relation-p01] An *equivalence relation* is a relation that is reflexive, symmetric, and transitive.
[src:discrete-mathematics/binary-relation-p01] All operations defined in section § Operations also apply to homogeneous relations.
[src:discrete-mathematics/binary-relation-p02] Developments in algebraic logic have facilitated usage of binary relations.
[src:discrete-mathematics/binary-relation-p02] The calculus of relations includes the algebra of sets, extended by composition of relations and the use of converse relations.
[src:discrete-mathematics/binary-relation-p02] The inclusion R ⊆ S , {\displaystyle R\subseteq S,} ({\displaystyle R\subseteq S,}) meaning that a R b {\displaystyle aRb} ({\displaystyle aRb}) implies a S b {\displaystyle aSb} ({\displaystyle aSb}), sets the scene in a lattice of relations.
[src:discrete-mathematics/binary-relation-p02] But since P ⊆ Q ≡ ( P ∩ Q ¯ = ∅ ) ≡ ( P ∩ Q = P ) , {\displaystyle P\subseteq Q\equiv (P\cap {\bar {Q}}=\varnothing )\equiv (P\cap Q=P),} ({\displaystyle P\subseteq Q\equiv (P\cap {\bar {Q}}=\varnothing )\equiv (P\cap Q=P),}) the inclusion symbol is superfluous.
[src:discrete-mathematics/binary-relation-p02] In contrast to homogeneous relations, the composition of relations operation is only a partial function.
[src:discrete-mathematics/binary-relation-p02] The necessity of matching target to source of composed relations has led to the suggestion that the study of heterogeneous relations is a chapter of category theory as in the category of sets, except that the morphisms of this category are relations.
[src:discrete-mathematics/binary-relation-p02] The *objects* of the category Rel are sets, and the relation-morphisms compose as required in a category.
[src:discrete-mathematics/binary-relation-p02] The MacNeille completion theorem (1937) (that any partial order may be embedded in a complete lattice) is cited in a 2013 survey article "Decomposition of relations on concept lattices".
[src:discrete-mathematics/binary-relation-p02] or left-total, functional relations in this context.
[src:discrete-mathematics/binary-relation-p02] Particular cases are considered below: E {\displaystyle E} ({\displaystyle E}) total order corresponds to Ferrers type, and E {\displaystyle E} ({\displaystyle E}) identity corresponds to difunctional, a generalization of equivalence relation on a set.
[src:discrete-mathematics/binary-relation-p02] Relations may be ranked by the **Schein rank** which counts the number of concepts necessary to cover a relation.
[src:discrete-mathematics/binary-relation-p02] Structural analysis of relations with concepts provides an approach for data mining.
[src:discrete-mathematics/binary-relation-p02] The idea of a difunctional relation is to partition objects by distinguishing attributes, as a generalization of the concept of an equivalence relation.
[src:discrete-mathematics/binary-relation-p02] One way this can be done is with an intervening set Z = { x , y , z , … } {\displaystyle Z=\{x,y,z,\ldots \}} ({\displaystyle Z=\{x,y,z,\ldots \}}) of indicators.
[src:discrete-mathematics/binary-relation-p02] In automata theory, the term **rectangular relation** has also been used to denote a difunctional relation.
[src:discrete-mathematics/binary-relation-p02] This terminology recalls the fact that, when represented as a logical matrix, the columns and rows of a difunctional relation can be arranged as a block matrix with rectangular blocks of ones on the (asymmetric) main diagonal.
[src:discrete-mathematics/binary-relation-p02] In 1997 researchers found "utility of binary decomposition based on difunctional dependencies in database management." Furthermore, difunctional relations are fundamental in the study of bisimulations.
[src:discrete-mathematics/binary-relation-p02] In the context of homogeneous relations, a partial equivalence relation is difunctional.
[src:discrete-mathematics/binary-relation-p02] A strict order on a set is a homogeneous relation arising in order theory.
[src:discrete-mathematics/binary-relation-p02] In 1951 Jacques Riguet adopted the ordering of an integer partition, called a Ferrers diagram, to extend ordering to binary relations in general.
[src:discrete-mathematics/binary-relation-p02] The corresponding logical matrix of a general binary relation has rows which finish with a sequence of ones.
[src:discrete-mathematics/binary-relation-p02] Thus the dots of a Ferrer's diagram are changed to ones and aligned on the right in the matrix.
[src:discrete-mathematics/binary-relation-p02] If any one of the relations R , R ¯ , R T {\displaystyle R,{\bar {R}},R^{\textsf {T}}} ({\displaystyle R,{\bar {R}},R^{\textsf {T}}}) is of Ferrers type, then all of them are.
[src:discrete-mathematics/binary-relation-p02] Suppose B {\displaystyle B} ({\displaystyle B}) is the power set of A {\displaystyle A} ({\displaystyle A}), the set of all subsets of A {\displaystyle A} ({\displaystyle A}).
[src:discrete-mathematics/binary-relation-p02] The set membership relation, ϵ = {\displaystyle \epsilon =} ({\displaystyle \epsilon =}) "is an element of", satisfies these properties so ϵ {\displaystyle \epsilon } ({\displaystyle \epsilon }) is a contact relation.
[src:discrete-mathematics/binary-relation-p02] The notion of a general contact relation was introduced by Georg Aumann in 1970.
[src:discrete-mathematics/binary-relation-p02] Every relation R {\displaystyle R} ({\displaystyle R}) generates a preorder R ∖ R {\displaystyle R\backslash R} ({\displaystyle R\backslash R}) which is the left residual.
[src:discrete-mathematics/binary-relation-p02] When R {\displaystyle R} ({\displaystyle R}) is a partial identity relation, difunctional, or a block diagonal relation, then fringe ⁡ ( R ) = R {\displaystyle \operatorname {fringe} (R)=R} ({\displaystyle \operatorname {fringe} (R)=R}).
[src:discrete-mathematics/binary-relation-p02] On the other hand, fringe ⁡ ( R ) = ∅ {\displaystyle \operatorname {fringe} (R)=\emptyset } ({\displaystyle \operatorname {fringe} (R)=\emptyset }) when R {\displaystyle R} ({\displaystyle R}) is a dense, linear, strict order.
[src:discrete-mathematics/binary-relation-p02] In 1953 Viktor Wagner used properties of this ternary operation to define semiheaps, heaps, and generalized heaps.
[src:discrete-mathematics/binary-relation] Precisely, a binary relation over sets X and Y is a set of ordered pairs $(x,y)$ , where x is an element of X and y is an element of Y .
[src:discrete-mathematics/binary-relation] It encodes the common concept of relation: an element x is *related* to an element y if and only if the pair $(x,y)$ belongs to the set of ordered pairs that defines the binary relation.
[src:discrete-mathematics/binary-relation] An example of a binary relation is the "divides" relation over the set of prime numbers $\mathbb {P}$ and the set of integers $\mathbb {Z}$ , in which each prime p is related to each integer z that is a multiple of p , but not to an integer that is not a multiple of p .
[src:discrete-mathematics/binary-relation] In this relation, for instance, the prime number 2 is related to numbers such as $-4$ , 0 , 6 , $10$ , but not to 1 or 9 , just as the prime number 3 is related to 0 , 6 , and 9 , but not to 4 or $13$ .
[src:discrete-mathematics/binary-relation] A binary relation is called a homogeneous relation when $X=Y$ .
[src:discrete-mathematics/binary-relation] A binary relation is also called a *heterogeneous relation* when it is not necessary that $X=Y$ .
[src:discrete-mathematics/binary-relation] Given sets X and Y , the Cartesian product $X\times Y$ is defined as $\{(x,y)\mid x\in X{\text{ and }}y\in Y\},$ and its elements are called *ordered pairs*.
[src:discrete-mathematics/binary-relation] A *binary relation* R over sets X and Y is a subset of $X\times Y.$ The set X is called the *domain* or *set of departure* of R , and the set Y the *codomain* or *set of destination* of R .
[src:discrete-mathematics/binary-relation] In order to specify the choices of the sets X and Y , some authors define a *binary relation* or *correspondence* as an ordered triple $(X,Y,G)$ , where G is a subset of $X\times Y$ called the *graph* of the binary relation.
[src:discrete-mathematics/binary-relation] The statement $(x,y)\in R$ reads " x is R -related to y " and is denoted by $xRy$ .
[src:discrete-mathematics/binary-relation] The *domain of definition* or *active domain* of R is the set of all x such that $xRy$ for at least one y .
[src:discrete-mathematics/binary-relation] The *codomain of definition*, *active codomain*, *image* or *range* of R is the set of all y such that $xRy$ for at least one x .
[src:discrete-mathematics/binary-relation] The *field* of R is the union of its domain of definition and its codomain of definition.
[src:discrete-mathematics/binary-relation] When $X=Y,$ a binary relation is called a *homogeneous relation* (or *endorelation*).
[src:discrete-mathematics/binary-relation] To emphasize the fact that X and Y are allowed to be different, a binary relation is also called a **heterogeneous relation**.
[src:discrete-mathematics/binary-relation] In a binary relation, the order of the elements is important; if $x\neq y$ then $yRx$ can be true or false independently of $xRy$ .
[src:discrete-mathematics/binary-relation] For example, 3 divides 9 , but 9 does not divide 3 .
[src:discrete-mathematics/binary-relation] If R and S are binary relations over sets X and Y then $R\cup S=\{(x,y)\mid xRy{\text{ or }}xSy\}$ is the *union relation* of R and S over X and Y .
[src:discrete-mathematics/binary-relation] The identity element is the empty relation, in which no x is related to any y .
[src:discrete-mathematics/binary-relation] For example, $\leq$ is the union of < and = , and $\geq$ is the union of > and = .
[src:discrete-mathematics/binary-relation] If R and S are binary relations over sets X and Y then $R\cap S=\{(x,y)\mid xRy{\text{ and }}xSy\}$ is the *intersection relation* of R and S over X and Y .
[src:discrete-mathematics/binary-relation] The identity element is the universal relation, in which every x is related to every y .
[src:discrete-mathematics/binary-relation] If R is a binary relation over sets X and Y , and S is a binary relation over sets Y and Z then $S\circ R=\{(x,z)\mid {\text{ there exists }}y\in Y{\text{ such that }}xRy{\text{ and }}ySz\}$ (also denoted by $R;S$ ) is the *composition relation* of R and S over X and Z .
[src:discrete-mathematics/binary-relation] If $X=Y=Z$ , the identity element w.r.t. composition is the identity relation on X , in which $x\in X$ is related only to itself.
[src:discrete-mathematics/binary-relation] The order of R and S in the notation $S\circ R$ used here agrees with the standard notational order for composition of functions.
[src:discrete-mathematics/binary-relation] For example, the composition (is parent of) $\circ$ (is mother of) yields (is grandmother of), while the composition (is mother of) $\circ$ (is parent of) yields (is maternal grandparent of).
[src:discrete-mathematics/binary-relation] For the latter case, if x is the parent of y and y is the mother of z , then x is the maternal grandparent of z .
[src:discrete-mathematics/binary-relation] If R is a binary relation over sets X and Y then $R^{\textsf {T}}=\{(y,x)\mid xRy\}$ is the *converse relation*, also called *inverse relation*, of R over Y and X .
[src:discrete-mathematics/binary-relation] For example, = is the converse of itself, as is $\neq$ , and < and > are each other's converse, as are $\leq$ and $\geq .$ A binary relation is equal to its converse if and only if it is symmetric.
[src:discrete-mathematics/binary-relation] If R is a binary relation over sets X and Y then ${\bar {R}}=\{(x,y)\mid \neg xRy\}$ (also denoted by $\neg R$ ) is the *complementary relation* of R over X and Y .
[src:discrete-mathematics/binary-relation] For example, = and $\neq$ are each other's complement, as are $\subseteq$ and $\not \subseteq$ , $\supseteq$ and $\not \supseteq$ , $\in$ and $\not \in$ , and for total orders also < and $\geq$ , and > and $\leq$ .
[src:discrete-mathematics/binary-relation] If R is a binary homogeneous relation over a set X and S is a subset of X then $R_{\vert S}=\{(x,y)\mid xRy{\text{ and }}x\in S{\text{ and }}y\in S\}$ is the *restriction relation* of R to S over X .
[src:discrete-mathematics/binary-relation] If R is a binary relation over sets X and Y and if S is a subset of X then $R_{\vert S}=\{(x,y)\mid xRy{\text{ and }}x\in S\}$ is the *left-restriction relation* of R to S over X and Y .
[src:discrete-mathematics/binary-relation] For example, restricting the relation " x is parent of y " to females yields the relation " x is mother of the woman y "; its transitive closure does not relate a woman with her paternal grandmother.
[src:discrete-mathematics/binary-relation] A binary relation R over sets X and Y is said to be *contained in* a relation S over X and Y , written $R\subseteq S,$ if R is a subset of S , that is, for all $x\in X$ and $y\in Y,$ if $xRy$ , then $xSy$ .
[src:discrete-mathematics/binary-relation] If R is contained in S and S is contained in R , then R and S are called *equal* written $R=S$ .
[src:discrete-mathematics/binary-relation] If R is contained in S but S is not contained in R , then R is said to be *smaller* than S , written $R\subsetneq S.$ For example, on the rational numbers, the relation > is smaller than $\geq$ , and equal to the composition $>\circ >$ .
[src:discrete-mathematics/binary-relation] Homogeneous relations (when $X=Y$ ) form a matrix semiring (indeed, a matrix semialgebra over the Boolean semiring) where the identity matrix corresponds to the identity relation.
[src:discrete-mathematics/binary-relation] Let $aRb$ represent that ocean a borders continent b .
[src:discrete-mathematics/binary-relation] On the other hand, $R^{\mathsf {T}}R$ is a relation on $B\times B$ which *fails* to be universal because at least two oceans must be traversed to voyage from Europe to Australia.
[src:discrete-mathematics/binary-relation] The idea of *simultaneous events* is simple in absolute space and time since each time t determines a simultaneous hyperplane in that cosmology.
[src:discrete-mathematics/binary-relation] The indefinite inner product in a composition algebra is given by $\langle x,z\rangle =x{\bar {z}}+{\bar {x}}z\;$ where the overbar denotes conjugation.
[src:discrete-mathematics/binary-relation] Jakob Steiner pioneered the cataloguing of configurations with the Steiner systems $\operatorname {S} (t,k,n)$ which have an n-element set $\operatorname {S}$ and a set of k-element subsets called **blocks**, such that a subset with t elements lies in just one block.
[src:discrete-mathematics/binary-relation] Some important types of binary relations R over sets X and Y are listed below.
[src:discrete-mathematics/binary-relation] For example, to model the general concept of "equality" as a binary relation = , take the domain and codomain to be the "class of all sets", which is not a set in the usual set theory.
[src:discrete-mathematics/binary-relation] The usual work-around to this problem is to select a "large enough" set A , that contains all the objects of interest, and work with the restriction $=_{A}$ instead of = .
[src:discrete-mathematics/binary-relation] Bertrand Russell has shown that assuming $\in$ to be defined over all sets leads to a contradiction in naive set theory, see *Russell's paradox*.
[src:discrete-mathematics/binary-relation] A **homogeneous relation** over a set X is a binary relation over X and itself, i.e. it is a subset of the Cartesian product $X\times X.$ It is also simply called a (binary) relation over X .
[src:discrete-mathematics/binary-relation] A homogeneous relation R over a set X may be identified with a directed simple graph permitting loops, where X is the vertex set and R is the edge set (there is an edge from a vertex x to a vertex y if and only if $xRy$ ).
[src:discrete-mathematics/binary-relation] The set of all homogeneous relations ${\mathcal {B}}(X)$ over a set X is the power set $2^{X\times X}$ which is a Boolean algebra augmented with the involution of mapping of a relation to its converse relation.
[src:discrete-mathematics/binary-relation] Considering composition of relations as a binary operation on ${\mathcal {B}}(X)$ , it forms a semigroup with involution.
[src:discrete-mathematics/binary-relation] For example, " x divides y " is a partial, but not a total order on natural numbers $\mathbb {N} ,$ " $x<y$ " is a strict total order on $\mathbb {N} ,$ and " x is parallel to y " is an equivalence relation on the set of all lines in the Euclidean plane.
[src:discrete-mathematics/binary-relation] The inclusion $R\subseteq S,$ meaning that $aRb$ implies $aSb$ , sets the scene in a lattice of relations.
[src:discrete-mathematics/binary-relation] But since $P\subseteq Q\equiv (P\cap {\bar {Q}}=\varnothing )\equiv (P\cap Q=P),$ the inclusion symbol is superfluous.
[src:discrete-mathematics/binary-relation] For a given relation $R\subseteq X\times Y,$ the set of concepts, enlarged by their joins and meets, forms an "induced lattice of concepts", with inclusion $\sqsubseteq$ forming a preorder.
[src:discrete-mathematics/binary-relation] Particular cases are considered below: E total order corresponds to Ferrers type, and E identity corresponds to difunctional, a generalization of equivalence relation on a set.
[src:discrete-mathematics/binary-relation] One way this can be done is with an intervening set $Z=\{x,y,z,\ldots \}$ of indicators.
[src:discrete-mathematics/binary-relation] More formally, a relation R on $X\times Y$ is difunctional if and only if it can be written as the union of Cartesian products $A_{i}\times B_{i}$ , where the $A_{i}$ are a partition of a subset of X and the $B_{i}$ likewise a partition of a subset of Y .
[src:discrete-mathematics/binary-relation] If any one of the relations $R,{\bar {R}},R^{\textsf {T}}$ is of Ferrers type, then all of them are.
[src:discrete-mathematics/binary-relation] Suppose B is the power set of A , the set of all subsets of A .
[src:discrete-mathematics/binary-relation] The set membership relation, $\epsilon =$ "is an element of", satisfies these properties so $\epsilon$ is a contact relation.
[src:discrete-mathematics/binary-relation] In terms of the calculus of relations, sufficient conditions for a contact relation include $C^{\textsf {T}}{\bar {C}}\subseteq \ni {\bar {C}}\equiv C{\overline {\ni {\bar {C}}}}\subseteq C,$ where $\ni$ is the converse of set membership ( $\in$ ).
[src:discrete-mathematics/binary-relation] Every relation R generates a preorder $R\backslash R$ which is the left residual.
[src:discrete-mathematics/binary-relation] In terms of converse and complements, $R\backslash R\equiv {\overline {R^{\textsf {T}}{\bar {R}}}}.$ Forming the diagonal of $R^{\textsf {T}}{\bar {R}}$ , the corresponding row of $R^{\textsf {T}}$ and column of ${\bar {R}}$ will be of opposite logical values, so the diagonal is all zeros.
[src:discrete-mathematics/binary-relation] When R is a partial identity relation, difunctional, or a block diagonal relation, then $\operatorname {fringe} (R)=R$ .
[src:discrete-mathematics/binary-relation] On the other hand, $\operatorname {fringe} (R)=\emptyset$ when R is a dense, linear, strict order.
[src:discrete-mathematics/binary-relation] Given two sets A and B , the set of binary relations between them ${\mathcal {B}}(A,B)$ can be equipped with a ternary operation $[a,b,c]=ab^{\textsf {T}}c$ where $b^{\mathsf {T}}$ denotes the converse relation of b .
[src:discrete-mathematics/combination] In mathematics, a **combination** is a selection of items from a set that has distinct members, such that the order of selection does not matter (unlike permutations).
[src:discrete-mathematics/combination] For example, given three fruits, say an apple, an orange and a pear, there are three combinations of two that can be drawn from this set: an apple and a pear; an apple and an orange; or a pear and an orange.
[src:discrete-mathematics/combination] More formally, a *k*-combination of a set *S* is a subset of *k* distinct elements of *S*.
[src:discrete-mathematics/combination] So, two combinations are identical if and only if each combination has the same members.
[src:discrete-mathematics/combination] This formula can be derived from the fact that each *k*-combination of a set *S* of *n* members has $k!$ permutations so $P_{k}^{n}=C_{k}^{n}\times k!$ or $C_{k}^{n}=P_{k}^{n}/k!$ .
[src:discrete-mathematics/combination] The set of all *k*-combinations of a set *S* is often denoted by $\textstyle {\binom {S}{k}}$ .
[src:discrete-mathematics/combination] A combination is a selection of *n* things taken *k* at a time *without repetition*.
[src:discrete-mathematics/combination] To refer to combinations in which repetition is allowed, the terms *k*-combination with repetition, *k*-multiset, or *k*-selection, are often used.
[src:discrete-mathematics/combination] If, in the above example, it were possible to have two of any one kind of fruit there would be 3 more 2-selections: one with two apples, one with two oranges, and one with two pears.
[src:discrete-mathematics/combination] Although the set of three fruits was small enough to write a complete list of combinations, this becomes impractical as the size of the set increases.
[src:discrete-mathematics/combination] For example, a poker hand can be described as a 5-combination (*k* = 5) of cards from a 52 card deck (*n* = 52).
[src:discrete-mathematics/combination] The 5 cards of the hand are all distinct, and the order of cards in the hand does not matter.
[src:discrete-mathematics/combination] There are 2,598,960 such combinations, and the chance of drawing any one hand at random is 1 / 2,598,960.
[src:discrete-mathematics/combination] The same number however occurs in many other mathematical contexts, where it is denoted by ${\tbinom {n}{k}}$ (often read as "*n* choose *k*"); notably it occurs as a coefficient in the binomial formula, hence its name binomial coefficient.
[src:discrete-mathematics/combination] it has 2*n* distinct terms corresponding to all the subsets of *S*, each subset giving the product of the corresponding variables *X**s*.
[src:discrete-mathematics/combination] Now setting all of the *X**s* equal to the unlabeled variable *X*, so that the product becomes (1 + *X*)*n*, the term for each *k*-combination from *S* becomes *X**k*, so that the coefficient of that power in the result equals the number of such *k*-combinations.
[src:discrete-mathematics/combination] Binomial coefficients can be computed explicitly in various ways.
[src:discrete-mathematics/combination] for 0 < *k* < *n*, which follows from (1 + *X*)*n* = (1 + *X*)*n* − 1(1 + *X*); this leads to the construction of Pascal's triangle.
[src:discrete-mathematics/combination] The numerator gives the number of *k*-permutations of *n*, i.e., of sequences of *k* distinct elements of *S*, while the denominator gives the number of such *k*-permutations that give the same *k*-combination when the order is ignored.
[src:discrete-mathematics/combination] This expresses a symmetry that is evident from the binomial formula, and can also be understood in terms of *k*-combinations by taking the complement of such a combination, which is an (*n* − *k*)-combination.
[src:discrete-mathematics/combination] where *n*! denotes the factorial of *n*.
[src:discrete-mathematics/combination] It is obtained from the previous formula by multiplying denominator and numerator by (*n* − *k*)!, so it is certainly computationally less efficient than that formula.
[src:discrete-mathematics/combination] The last formula can be understood directly, by considering the *n*! permutations of all the elements of *S*.
[src:discrete-mathematics/combination] Each such permutation gives a *k*-combination by selecting its first *k* elements.
[src:discrete-mathematics/combination] There are many duplicate selections: any combined permutation of the first *k* elements among each other, and of the final (*n* − *k*) elements among each other produces the same combination; this explains the division in the formula.
[src:discrete-mathematics/combination] When evaluated in the following order, 52 ÷ 1 × 51 ÷ 2 × 50 ÷ 3 × 49 ÷ 4 × 48 ÷ 5, this can be computed using only integer arithmetic.
[src:discrete-mathematics/combination] The reason is that when each division occurs, the intermediate result that is produced is itself a binomial coefficient, so no remainders ever occur.
[src:discrete-mathematics/combination] One can enumerate all *k*-combinations of a given set *S* of *n* elements in some fixed order, which establishes a bijection from an interval of ${\tbinom {n}{k}}$ integers with the set of those *k*-combinations.
[src:discrete-mathematics/combination] Assuming *S* is itself ordered, for instance *S* = { 1, 2, ..., *n* }, there are two natural possibilities for ordering its *k*-combinations: by comparing their smallest elements first (as in the illustrations above) or by comparing their largest elements first.
[src:discrete-mathematics/combination] The latter option has the advantage that adding a new largest element to *S* will not change the initial part of the enumeration, but just add the new *k*-combinations of the larger set after the previous ones.
[src:discrete-mathematics/combination] Repeating this process, the enumeration can be extended indefinitely with *k*-combinations of ever larger sets.
[src:discrete-mathematics/combination] If moreover the intervals of the integers are taken to start at 0, then the *k*-combination at a given place *i* in the enumeration can be computed easily from *i*, and the bijection so obtained is known as the combinatorial number system.
[src:discrete-mathematics/combination] It is also known as "rank"/"ranking" and "unranking" in computational mathematics.
[src:discrete-mathematics/combination] There are many ways to enumerate *k* combinations.
[src:discrete-mathematics/combination] One way is to track *k* index numbers of the elements selected, starting with {0 ..
[src:discrete-mathematics/combination] *k*} (one-based) as the first allowed *k*-combination.
[src:discrete-mathematics/combination] Then, repeatedly move to the next allowed *k*-combination by incrementing the smallest index number for which this would not create two equal index numbers, at the same time resetting all smaller index numbers to their initial values.
[src:discrete-mathematics/combination] In other words, it is a sample of *k* elements from a set of *n* elements allowing for duplicates (i.e., with replacement) but disregarding different orderings (e.g. {2,1,2} = {1,2,2}).
[src:discrete-mathematics/combination] Associate an index to each element of *S* and think of the elements of *S* as *types* of objects, then we can let $x_{i}$ denote the number of elements of type *i* in a multisubset.
[src:discrete-mathematics/combination] a notation that is analogous to the binomial coefficient which counts *k*-subsets.
[src:discrete-mathematics/combination] This relationship can be easily proved using a representation known as stars and bars.
[src:discrete-mathematics/combination] A solution of the above Diophantine equation can be represented by $x_{1}$ *stars*, a separator (a *bar*), then $x_{2}$ more stars, another separator, and so on.
[src:discrete-mathematics/combination] The total number of stars in this representation is *k* and the number of bars is *n* - 1 (since a separation into n parts needs n-1 separators).
[src:discrete-mathematics/combination] Thus, a string of *k* + *n* - 1 (or *n* + *k* - 1) symbols (stars and bars) corresponds to a solution if there are *k* stars in the string.
[src:discrete-mathematics/combination] Any solution can be represented by choosing *k* out of *k* + *n* − 1 positions to place stars and filling the remaining positions with bars.
[src:discrete-mathematics/combination] The number of such strings is the number of ways to place 10 stars in 13 positions, ${\textstyle {\binom {13}{10}}={\binom {13}{3}}=286,}$ which is the number of 10-multisubsets of a set with 4 elements.
[src:discrete-mathematics/combination] As with binomial coefficients, there are several relationships between these multichoose expressions.
[src:discrete-mathematics/combination] $\left(\!\!{\binom {n}{k}}\!\!\right)=\left(\!\!{\binom {k+1}{n-1}}\!\!\right).$ This identity follows from interchanging the stars and bars in the above representation.
[src:discrete-mathematics/combination] This result can be verified by listing all the 3-multisubsets of the set *S* = {1,2,3,4}.
[src:discrete-mathematics/combination] This is displayed in the following table.
[src:discrete-mathematics/combination] The second column lists the donuts you actually chose, the third column shows the nonnegative integer solutions $[x_{1},x_{2},x_{3},x_{4}]$ of the equation $x_{1}+x_{2}+x_{3}+x_{4}=3$ and the last column gives the stars and bars representation of the solutions.
[src:discrete-mathematics/combination] The number of *k*-combinations for all *k* is the number of subsets of a set of *n* elements.
[src:discrete-mathematics/combination] There are several ways to see that this number is 2*n*.
[src:discrete-mathematics/combination] In terms of combinations, ${\textstyle \sum _{0\leq {k}\leq {n}}{\binom {n}{k}}=2^{n}}$ , which is the sum of the *n*th row (counting from 0) of the binomial coefficients in Pascal's triangle.
[src:discrete-mathematics/combination] These combinations (subsets) are enumerated by the 1 digits of the set of base 2 numbers counting from 0 to 2*n* − 1, where each digit position is an item from the set of *n*.
[src:discrete-mathematics/combination] There are various algorithms to pick out a random combination from a given set or list.
[src:discrete-mathematics/combination] Rejection sampling is extremely slow for large sample sizes.
[src:discrete-mathematics/combination] Another is to pick a random non-negative integer less than $\textstyle {\binom {n}{k}}$ and convert it into a combination using the combinatorial number system.
[src:discrete-mathematics/combination] A combination can also be thought of as a selection of *two* sets of items: those that go into the chosen bin and those that go into the unchosen bin.
[src:discrete-mathematics/combination] This can be generalized to any number of bins with the constraint that every item must go to exactly one bin.
[src:discrete-mathematics/combination] where *n* is the number of items, *m* is the number of bins, and $k_{i}$ is the number of items that go into bin *i*.
[src:discrete-mathematics/combination] One way to see why this equation holds is to first number the objects arbitrarily from *1* to *n* and put the objects with numbers $1,2,\ldots ,k_{1}$ into the first bin in order, the objects with numbers $k_{1}+1,k_{1}+2,\ldots ,k_{1}+k_{2}$ into the second bin in order, and so on.
[src:discrete-mathematics/combination] There are $n!$ distinct numberings, but many of them are equivalent, because only the set of items in a bin matters, not their order in it.
[src:discrete-mathematics/combination] Every combined permutation of each bins' contents produces an equivalent way of putting items into bins.
[src:discrete-mathematics/combination] As a result, every equivalence class consists of $k_{1}!\,k_{2}!\cdots k_{m}!$ distinct numberings, and the number of equivalence classes is $\textstyle {\frac {n!}{k_{1}!\,k_{2}!\cdots k_{m}!}}$ .
[src:discrete-mathematics/combinatorics] Combinatorics is well known for the breadth of the problems it tackles.
[src:discrete-mathematics/combinatorics] Combinatorial problems arise in many areas of pure mathematics, notably in algebra, probability theory, topology, and geometry, as well as in its many application areas.
[src:discrete-mathematics/combinatorics] Many combinatorial questions have historically been considered in isolation, giving an *ad hoc* solution to a problem arising in some mathematical context.
[src:discrete-mathematics/combinatorics] In the later twentieth century, however, powerful and general theoretical methods were developed, making combinatorics into an independent branch of mathematics in its own right.
[src:discrete-mathematics/combinatorics] One of the oldest and most accessible parts of combinatorics is graph theory, which by itself has numerous natural connections to other areas.
[src:discrete-mathematics/combinatorics] Combinatorics is used frequently in computer science to obtain formulas and estimates in the analysis of algorithms.
[src:discrete-mathematics/combinatorics] The full scope of combinatorics is not universally agreed upon.
[src:discrete-mathematics/combinatorics] Ryser, a definition of the subject is difficult because it crosses so many mathematical subdivisions.
[src:discrete-mathematics/combinatorics] This is the approach that is used below.
[src:discrete-mathematics/combinatorics] However, there are also purely historical reasons for including or not including some topics under the combinatorics umbrella.
[src:discrete-mathematics/combinatorics] Although primarily concerned with finite systems, some combinatorial questions and techniques can be extended to an infinite (specifically, countable) but discrete setting.
[src:discrete-mathematics/combinatorics] Basic combinatorial concepts and enumerative results appeared throughout the ancient world.
[src:discrete-mathematics/combinatorics] The earliest recorded use of combinatorial techniques comes from problem 79 of the Rhind papyrus, which dates to the 16th century BC.
[src:discrete-mathematics/combinatorics] The problem concerns a certain geometric series, and has similarities to Fibonacci's problem of counting the number of compositions of 1s and 2s that sum to a given total.
[src:discrete-mathematics/combinatorics] Indian physician Sushruta asserts in *Sushruta Samhita* that 63 combinations can be made out of 6 different tastes, taken one at a time, two at a time, etc., thus computing all 26 − 1 possibilities.
[src:discrete-mathematics/combinatorics] Greek historian Plutarch discusses an argument between Chrysippus (3rd century BCE) and Hipparchus (2nd century BCE) of a rather delicate enumerative problem, which was later shown to be related to Schröder–Hipparchus numbers.
[src:discrete-mathematics/combinatorics] Earlier, in the *Ostomachion*, Archimedes (3rd century BCE) may have considered the number of configurations of a tiling puzzle, while combinatorial interests possibly were present in lost works by Apollonius.
[src:discrete-mathematics/combinatorics] In the Middle Ages, combinatorics continued to be studied, largely outside of the European civilization.
[src:discrete-mathematics/combinatorics] 850) provided formulae for the number of permutations and combinations, and these formulas may have been familiar to Indian mathematicians as early as the 6th century CE.
[src:discrete-mathematics/combinatorics] The philosopher and astronomer Rabbi Abraham ibn Ezra (c.
[src:discrete-mathematics/combinatorics] 1140) established the symmetry of binomial coefficients, while a closed formula was obtained later by the talmudist and mathematician Levi ben Gerson (better known as Gersonides), in 1321.
[src:discrete-mathematics/combinatorics] The arithmetical triangle—a graphical diagram showing relationships among the binomial coefficients—was presented by mathematicians in treatises dating as far back as the 10th century, and would eventually become known as Pascal's triangle.
[src:discrete-mathematics/combinatorics] Later, in Medieval England, campanology provided examples of what is now known as Hamiltonian cycles in certain Cayley graphs on permutations.
[src:discrete-mathematics/combinatorics] During the Renaissance, together with the rest of mathematics and the sciences, combinatorics enjoyed a rebirth.
[src:discrete-mathematics/combinatorics] Works of Pascal, Newton, Jacob Bernoulli and Leonhard Euler became foundational in the emerging field.
[src:discrete-mathematics/combinatorics] Sylvester (late 19th century) and Percy MacMahon (early 20th century) helped lay the foundation for enumerative and algebraic combinatorics.
[src:discrete-mathematics/combinatorics] Graph theory also enjoyed an increase of interest at the same time, especially in connection with the four color problem.
[src:discrete-mathematics/combinatorics] In the second half of the 20th century, combinatorics enjoyed a rapid growth, which led to establishment of dozens of new journals and conferences in the subject.
[src:discrete-mathematics/combinatorics] In part, the growth was spurred by new connections and applications to other fields, ranging from algebra to probability, from functional analysis to number theory, etc.
[src:discrete-mathematics/combinatorics] These connections shed the boundaries between combinatorics and parts of mathematics and theoretical computer science, but at the same time led to a partial fragmentation of the field.
[src:discrete-mathematics/combinatorics] Enumerative combinatorics is the most classical area of combinatorics and concentrates on counting the number of certain combinatorial objects.
[src:discrete-mathematics/combinatorics] Although counting the number of elements in a set is a rather broad mathematical problem, many of the problems that arise in applications have a relatively simple combinatorial description.
[src:discrete-mathematics/combinatorics] Fibonacci numbers is the basic example of a problem in enumerative combinatorics.
[src:discrete-mathematics/combinatorics] The twelvefold way provides a unified framework for counting permutations, combinations and partitions.
[src:discrete-mathematics/combinatorics] Analytic combinatorics concerns the enumeration of combinatorial structures using tools from complex analysis and probability theory.
[src:discrete-mathematics/combinatorics] In contrast with enumerative combinatorics, which uses explicit combinatorial formulae and generating functions to describe the results, analytic combinatorics aims at obtaining asymptotic formulae.
[src:discrete-mathematics/combinatorics] Partition theory studies various enumeration and asymptotic problems related to integer partitions, and is closely related to q-series, special functions and orthogonal polynomials.
[src:discrete-mathematics/combinatorics] Originally a part of number theory and analysis, it is now considered a part of combinatorics or an independent field.
[src:discrete-mathematics/combinatorics] It incorporates the bijective approach and various tools in analysis and analytic number theory and has connections with statistical mechanics.
[src:discrete-mathematics/combinatorics] Partitions can be graphically visualized with Young diagrams or Ferrers diagrams.
[src:discrete-mathematics/combinatorics] They occur in a number of branches of mathematics and physics, including the study of symmetric polynomials and of the symmetric group and in group representation theory in general.
[src:discrete-mathematics/combinatorics] Graphs are fundamental objects in combinatorics.
[src:discrete-mathematics/combinatorics] Although there are very strong connections between graph theory and combinatorics, they are sometimes thought of as separate subjects.
[src:discrete-mathematics/combinatorics] While combinatorial methods apply to many graph theory problems, the two disciplines are generally used to seek solutions to different types of problems.
[src:discrete-mathematics/combinatorics] Design theory is a study of combinatorial designs, which are collections of subsets with certain intersection properties.
[src:discrete-mathematics/combinatorics] Block designs are combinatorial designs of a special type.
[src:discrete-mathematics/combinatorics] This area is one of the oldest parts of combinatorics, such as in Kirkman's schoolgirl problem proposed in 1850.
[src:discrete-mathematics/combinatorics] The solution of the problem is a special case of a Steiner system, which play an important role in the classification of finite simple groups.
[src:discrete-mathematics/combinatorics] The area has further connections to coding theory and geometric combinatorics.
[src:discrete-mathematics/combinatorics] Combinatorial design theory can be applied to the area of design of experiments.
[src:discrete-mathematics/combinatorics] Some of the basic theory of combinatorial designs originated in the statistician Ronald Fisher's work on the design of biological experiments.
[src:discrete-mathematics/combinatorics] Modern applications are also found in a wide gamut of areas including finite geometry, tournament scheduling, lotteries, mathematical chemistry, mathematical biology, algorithm design and analysis, networking, group testing and cryptography.
[src:discrete-mathematics/combinatorics] Finite geometry is the study of geometric systems having only a finite number of points.
[src:discrete-mathematics/combinatorics] Structures analogous to those found in continuous geometries (Euclidean plane, real projective space, etc.) but defined combinatorially are the main items studied.
[src:discrete-mathematics/combinatorics] This area provides a rich source of examples for design theory.
[src:discrete-mathematics/combinatorics] It should not be confused with discrete geometry (combinatorial geometry).
[src:discrete-mathematics/combinatorics] Order theory is the study of partially ordered sets, both finite and infinite.
[src:discrete-mathematics/combinatorics] It provides a formal framework for describing statements such as "this is less than that" or "this precedes that".
[src:discrete-mathematics/combinatorics] Various examples of partial orders appear in algebra, geometry, number theory and throughout combinatorics and graph theory.
[src:discrete-mathematics/combinatorics] Notable classes and examples of partial orders include lattices and Boolean algebras.
[src:discrete-mathematics/combinatorics] Matroid theory abstracts part of geometry.
[src:discrete-mathematics/combinatorics] It studies the properties of sets (usually, finite sets) of vectors in a vector space that do not depend on the particular coefficients in a linear dependence relation.
[src:discrete-mathematics/combinatorics] Not only the structure but also enumerative properties belong to matroid theory.
[src:discrete-mathematics/combinatorics] Matroid theory was introduced by Hassler Whitney and studied as a part of order theory.
[src:discrete-mathematics/combinatorics] It is now an independent field of study with a number of connections with other parts of combinatorics.
[src:discrete-mathematics/combinatorics] Extremal combinatorics studies how large or how small a collection of finite objects (numbers, graphs, vectors, sets, etc.) can be, if it has to satisfy certain restrictions.
[src:discrete-mathematics/combinatorics] Much of extremal combinatorics concerns classes of set systems; this is called extremal set theory.
[src:discrete-mathematics/combinatorics] For instance, in an *n*-element set, what is the largest number of *k*-element subsets that can pairwise intersect one another?
[src:discrete-mathematics/combinatorics] What is the largest number of subsets of which none contains any other?
[src:discrete-mathematics/combinatorics] The latter question is answered by Sperner's theorem, which gave rise to much of extremal set theory.
[src:discrete-mathematics/combinatorics] The types of questions addressed in this case are about the largest possible graph which satisfies certain properties.
[src:discrete-mathematics/combinatorics] For example, the largest triangle-free graph on *2n* vertices is a complete bipartite graph *Kn,n*.
[src:discrete-mathematics/combinatorics] Often it is too hard even to find the extremal answer *f*(*n*) exactly and one can only give an asymptotic estimate.
[src:discrete-mathematics/combinatorics] Ramsey theory is another part of extremal combinatorics.
[src:discrete-mathematics/combinatorics] It states that any sufficiently large configuration will contain some sort of order.
[src:discrete-mathematics/combinatorics] It is an advanced generalization of the pigeonhole principle.
[src:discrete-mathematics/combinatorics] In probabilistic combinatorics, the questions are of the following type: what is the probability of a certain property for a random discrete object, such as a random graph?
[src:discrete-mathematics/combinatorics] For instance, what is the average number of triangles in a random graph?
[src:discrete-mathematics/combinatorics] Probabilistic methods are also used to determine the existence of combinatorial objects with certain prescribed properties (for which explicit examples might be difficult to find) by observing that the probability of randomly selecting an object with those properties is greater than 0.
[src:discrete-mathematics/combinatorics] This approach (often referred to as *the* probabilistic method) proved highly effective in applications to extremal combinatorics and graph theory.
[src:discrete-mathematics/combinatorics] A closely related area is the study of finite Markov chains, especially on combinatorial objects.
[src:discrete-mathematics/combinatorics] Here again probabilistic tools are used to estimate the mixing time.
[src:discrete-mathematics/combinatorics] Often associated with Paul Erdős, who did the pioneering work on the subject, probabilistic combinatorics was traditionally viewed as a set of tools to study problems in other parts of combinatorics.
[src:discrete-mathematics/combinatorics] The area recently grew to become an independent field of combinatorics.
[src:discrete-mathematics/combinatorics] Algebraic combinatorics is an area of mathematics that employs methods of abstract algebra, notably group theory and representation theory, in various combinatorial contexts and, conversely, applies combinatorial techniques to problems in algebra.
[src:discrete-mathematics/combinatorics] Algebraic combinatorics has come to be seen more expansively as an area of mathematics where the interaction of combinatorial and algebraic methods is particularly strong and significant.
[src:discrete-mathematics/combinatorics] Thus the combinatorial topics may be enumerative in nature or involve matroids, polytopes, partially ordered sets, or finite geometries.
[src:discrete-mathematics/combinatorics] On the algebraic side, besides group and representation theory, lattice theory and commutative algebra are common.
[src:discrete-mathematics/combinatorics] Combinatorics on words deals with formal languages.
[src:discrete-mathematics/combinatorics] It arose independently within several branches of mathematics, including number theory, group theory and probability.
[src:discrete-mathematics/combinatorics] It has applications to enumerative combinatorics, fractal analysis, theoretical computer science, automata theory, and linguistics.
[src:discrete-mathematics/combinatorics] While many applications are new, the classical Chomsky–Schützenberger hierarchy of classes of formal grammars is perhaps the best-known result in the field.
[src:discrete-mathematics/combinatorics] Geometric combinatorics is related to convex and discrete geometry.
[src:discrete-mathematics/combinatorics] It asks, for example, how many faces of each dimension a convex polytope can have.
[src:discrete-mathematics/combinatorics] Metric properties of polytopes play an important role as well, e.g. the Cauchy theorem on the rigidity of convex polytopes.
[src:discrete-mathematics/combinatorics] Special polytopes are also considered, such as permutohedra, associahedra and Birkhoff polytopes.
[src:discrete-mathematics/combinatorics] Combinatorial geometry is a historical name for discrete geometry.
[src:discrete-mathematics/combinatorics] It includes a number of subareas such as polyhedral combinatorics (the study of faces of convex polyhedra), convex geometry (the study of convex sets, in particular combinatorics of their intersections), and discrete geometry, which in turn has many applications to computational geometry.
[src:discrete-mathematics/combinatorics] The study of regular polytopes, Archimedean solids, and kissing numbers is also a part of geometric combinatorics.
[src:discrete-mathematics/combinatorics] Special polytopes are also considered, such as the permutohedron, associahedron and Birkhoff polytope.
[src:discrete-mathematics/combinatorics] Combinatorial analogs of concepts and methods in topology are used to study graph coloring, fair division, partitions, partially ordered sets, decision trees, necklace problems and discrete Morse theory.
[src:discrete-mathematics/combinatorics] It should not be confused with combinatorial topology which is an older name for algebraic topology.
[src:discrete-mathematics/combinatorics] Arithmetic combinatorics arose out of the interplay between number theory, combinatorics, ergodic theory, and harmonic analysis.
[src:discrete-mathematics/combinatorics] It is about combinatorial estimates associated with arithmetic operations (addition, subtraction, multiplication, and division).
[src:discrete-mathematics/combinatorics] Additive number theory (sometimes also called additive combinatorics) refers to the special case when only the operations of addition and subtraction are involved.
[src:discrete-mathematics/combinatorics] One important technique in arithmetic combinatorics is the ergodic theory of dynamical systems.
[src:discrete-mathematics/combinatorics] Infinitary combinatorics, or combinatorial set theory, is an extension of ideas in combinatorics to infinite sets.
[src:discrete-mathematics/combinatorics] It is a part of set theory, an area of mathematical logic, but uses tools and ideas from both set theory and extremal combinatorics.
[src:discrete-mathematics/combinatorics] Some of the things studied include continuous graphs and trees, extensions of Ramsey's theorem, and Martin's axiom.
[src:discrete-mathematics/combinatorics] Recent developments concern combinatorics of the continuum and combinatorics on successors of singular cardinals.
[src:discrete-mathematics/combinatorics] Gian-Carlo Rota used the name *continuous combinatorics* to describe geometric probability, since there are many analogies between *counting* and *measure*.
[src:discrete-mathematics/combinatorics] Combinatorial optimization is the study of optimization on discrete and combinatorial objects.
[src:discrete-mathematics/combinatorics] It started as a part of combinatorics and graph theory, but is now viewed as a branch of applied mathematics and computer science, related to operations research, algorithm theory and computational complexity theory.
[src:discrete-mathematics/combinatorics] Coding theory started as a part of design theory with early combinatorial constructions of error-correcting codes.
[src:discrete-mathematics/combinatorics] The main idea of the subject is to design efficient and reliable methods of data transmission.
[src:discrete-mathematics/combinatorics] It is now a large field of study, part of information theory.
[src:discrete-mathematics/combinatorics] Discrete geometry (also called combinatorial geometry) also began as a part of combinatorics, with early results on convex polytopes and kissing numbers.
[src:discrete-mathematics/combinatorics] With the emergence of applications of discrete geometry to computational geometry, these two fields partially merged and became a separate field of study.
[src:discrete-mathematics/combinatorics] There remain many connections with geometric and topological combinatorics, which themselves can be viewed as outgrowths of the early discrete geometry.
[src:discrete-mathematics/combinatorics] Combinatorial aspects of dynamical systems is another emerging field.
[src:discrete-mathematics/combinatorics] Here dynamical systems can be defined on combinatorial objects.
[src:discrete-mathematics/combinatorics] There are increasing interactions between combinatorics and physics, particularly statistical physics.
[src:discrete-mathematics/combinatorics] Examples include an exact solution of the Ising model, and a connection between the Potts model on one hand, and the chromatic and Tutte polynomials on the other hand.
[src:discrete-mathematics/discrete-mathematics] The set of objects studied in discrete mathematics can be finite or infinite.
[src:discrete-mathematics/discrete-mathematics] The term **finite mathematics** is sometimes applied to parts of the field of discrete mathematics that deal with finite sets, particularly those areas relevant to business.
[src:discrete-mathematics/discrete-mathematics] Research in discrete mathematics increased in the latter half of the twentieth century partly due to the development of digital computers which operate in "discrete" steps and store data in "discrete" bits.
[src:discrete-mathematics/discrete-mathematics] Concepts and notations from discrete mathematics are useful in studying and describing objects and problems in branches of computer science, such as computer algorithms, programming languages, cryptography, automated theorem proving, and software development.
[src:discrete-mathematics/discrete-mathematics] Conversely, computer implementations are significant in applying ideas from discrete mathematics to real-world problems.
[src:discrete-mathematics/discrete-mathematics] Although the main objects of study in discrete mathematics are discrete objects, analytic methods from "continuous" mathematics are often employed as well.
[src:discrete-mathematics/discrete-mathematics] In university curricula, discrete mathematics appeared in the 1980s, initially as a computer science support course; its contents were somewhat haphazard at the time.
[src:discrete-mathematics/discrete-mathematics] The curriculum has thereafter developed in conjunction with efforts by ACM and MAA into a course that is basically intended to develop mathematical maturity in first-year students; therefore, it is nowadays a prerequisite for mathematics majors in some universities as well.
[src:discrete-mathematics/discrete-mathematics] Some high-school-level discrete mathematics textbooks have appeared as well.
[src:discrete-mathematics/discrete-mathematics] At this level, discrete mathematics is sometimes seen as a preparatory course, like precalculus in this respect.
[src:discrete-mathematics/discrete-mathematics] The Fulkerson Prize is awarded for outstanding papers in discrete mathematics.
[src:discrete-mathematics/discrete-mathematics] Theoretical computer science includes areas of discrete mathematics relevant to computing.
[src:discrete-mathematics/discrete-mathematics] It draws heavily on graph theory and mathematical logic.
[src:discrete-mathematics/discrete-mathematics] Included within theoretical computer science is the study of algorithms and data structures.
[src:discrete-mathematics/discrete-mathematics] Computability studies what can be computed in principle, and has close ties to logic, while complexity studies the time, space, and other resources taken by computations.
[src:discrete-mathematics/discrete-mathematics] Automata theory and formal language theory are closely related to computability.
[src:discrete-mathematics/discrete-mathematics] Petri nets and process algebras are used to model computer systems, and methods from discrete mathematics are used in analyzing VLSI electronic circuits.
[src:discrete-mathematics/discrete-mathematics] Computational geometry applies algorithms to geometrical problems and representations of geometrical objects, while computer image analysis applies them to representations of images.
[src:discrete-mathematics/discrete-mathematics] Theoretical computer science also includes the study of various continuous computational topics.
[src:discrete-mathematics/discrete-mathematics] Information theory involves the quantification of information.
[src:discrete-mathematics/discrete-mathematics] Closely related is coding theory which is used to design efficient and reliable data transmission and storage methods.
[src:discrete-mathematics/discrete-mathematics] Information theory also includes continuous topics such as: analog signals, analog coding, analog encryption.
[src:discrete-mathematics/discrete-mathematics] Logic is the study of the principles of valid reasoning and inference, as well as of consistency, soundness, and completeness.
[src:discrete-mathematics/discrete-mathematics] For example, in most systems of logic (but not in intuitionistic logic) Peirce's law (((*P*→*Q*)→*P*)→*P*) is a theorem.
[src:discrete-mathematics/discrete-mathematics] For classical logic, it can be easily verified with a truth table.
[src:discrete-mathematics/discrete-mathematics] The study of mathematical proof is particularly important in logic, and has accumulated to automated theorem proving and formal verification of software.
[src:discrete-mathematics/discrete-mathematics] Logical formulas are discrete structures, as are proofs, which form finite trees or, more generally, directed acyclic graph structures (with each inference step combining one or more premise branches to give a single conclusion).
[src:discrete-mathematics/discrete-mathematics] The truth values of logical formulas usually form a finite set, generally restricted to two values: *true* and *false*, but logic can also be continuous-valued, e.g., fuzzy logic.
[src:discrete-mathematics/discrete-mathematics] Concepts such as infinite proof trees or infinite derivation trees have also been studied, e.g. infinitary logic.
[src:discrete-mathematics/discrete-mathematics] Set theory is the branch of mathematics that studies sets, which are collections of objects, such as {blue, white, red} or the (infinite) set of all prime numbers.
[src:discrete-mathematics/discrete-mathematics] Partially ordered sets and sets with other relations have applications in several areas.
[src:discrete-mathematics/discrete-mathematics] In discrete mathematics, countable sets (including finite sets) are the main focus.
[src:discrete-mathematics/discrete-mathematics] The beginning of set theory as a branch of mathematics is usually marked by Georg Cantor's work distinguishing between different kinds of infinite set, motivated by the study of trigonometric series, and further development of the theory of infinite sets is outside the scope of discrete mathematics.
[src:discrete-mathematics/discrete-mathematics] Indeed, contemporary work in descriptive set theory makes extensive use of traditional continuous mathematics.
[src:discrete-mathematics/discrete-mathematics] Combinatorics studies the ways in which discrete structures can be combined or arranged.
[src:discrete-mathematics/discrete-mathematics] Enumerative combinatorics concentrates on counting the number of certain combinatorial objects – e.g. the twelvefold way provides a unified framework for counting permutations, combinations and partitions.
[src:discrete-mathematics/discrete-mathematics] Analytic combinatorics concerns the enumeration (i.e., determining the number) of combinatorial structures using tools from complex analysis and probability theory.
[src:discrete-mathematics/discrete-mathematics] In contrast with enumerative combinatorics which uses explicit combinatorial formulae and generating functions to describe the results, analytic combinatorics aims at obtaining asymptotic formulae.
[src:discrete-mathematics/discrete-mathematics] Topological combinatorics concerns the use of techniques from topology and algebraic topology/combinatorial topology in combinatorics.
[src:discrete-mathematics/discrete-mathematics] Originally a part of number theory and analysis, partition theory is now considered a part of combinatorics or an independent field.
[src:discrete-mathematics/discrete-mathematics] Graph theory, the study of graphs and networks, is often considered part of combinatorics, but has grown large enough and distinct enough, with its own kind of problems, to be regarded as a subject in its own right.
[src:discrete-mathematics/discrete-mathematics] Graphs are one of the prime objects of study in discrete mathematics.
[src:discrete-mathematics/discrete-mathematics] They are among the most ubiquitous models of both natural and human-made structures.
[src:discrete-mathematics/discrete-mathematics] They can model many types of relations and process dynamics in physical, biological and social systems.
[src:discrete-mathematics/discrete-mathematics] In computer science, they can represent networks of communication, data organization, computational devices, the flow of computation, etc.
[src:discrete-mathematics/discrete-mathematics] In mathematics, they are useful in geometry and certain parts of topology, e.g. knot theory.
[src:discrete-mathematics/discrete-mathematics] Algebraic graph theory has close links with group theory and topological graph theory has close links to topology.
[src:discrete-mathematics/discrete-mathematics] There are also continuous graphs; however, for the most part, research in graph theory falls within the domain of discrete mathematics.
[src:discrete-mathematics/discrete-mathematics] Number theory is concerned with the properties of numbers in general, particularly integers.
[src:discrete-mathematics/discrete-mathematics] It has applications to cryptography and cryptanalysis, particularly with regard to modular arithmetic, diophantine equations, linear and quadratic congruences, prime numbers and primality testing.
[src:discrete-mathematics/discrete-mathematics] Other discrete aspects of number theory include geometry of numbers.
[src:discrete-mathematics/discrete-mathematics] In analytic number theory, techniques from continuous mathematics are also used.
[src:discrete-mathematics/discrete-mathematics] Topics that go beyond discrete objects include transcendental numbers, diophantine approximation, p-adic analysis and function fields.
[src:discrete-mathematics/discrete-mathematics] Algebraic structures occur as both discrete examples and continuous examples.
[src:discrete-mathematics/discrete-mathematics] Discrete algebras include: Boolean algebra used in logic gates and programming; relational algebra used in databases; discrete and finite versions of groups, rings and fields are important in algebraic coding theory; discrete semigroups and monoids appear in the theory of formal languages.
[src:discrete-mathematics/discrete-mathematics] In discrete calculus and the calculus of finite differences, a function defined on an interval of the integers is usually called a sequence.
[src:discrete-mathematics/discrete-mathematics] A sequence could be a finite sequence from a data source or an infinite sequence from a discrete dynamical system.
[src:discrete-mathematics/discrete-mathematics] Such a discrete function could be defined explicitly by a list (if its domain is finite), or by a formula for its general term, or it could be given implicitly by a recurrence relation or difference equation.
[src:discrete-mathematics/discrete-mathematics] Difference equations are similar to differential equations, but replace differentiation by taking the difference between adjacent terms; they can be used to approximate differential equations or (more often) studied in their own right.
[src:discrete-mathematics/discrete-mathematics] Many questions and methods concerning differential equations have counterparts for difference equations.
[src:discrete-mathematics/discrete-mathematics] For instance, where there are integral transforms in harmonic analysis for studying continuous functions or analogue signals, there are discrete transforms for discrete functions or digital signals.
[src:discrete-mathematics/discrete-mathematics] As well as discrete metric spaces, there are more general discrete topological spaces, finite metric spaces, finite topological spaces.
[src:discrete-mathematics/discrete-mathematics] The time scale calculus is a unification of the theory of difference equations with that of differential equations, which has applications to fields requiring simultaneous modelling of discrete and continuous data.
[src:discrete-mathematics/discrete-mathematics] Another way of modeling such a situation is the notion of hybrid dynamical systems.
[src:discrete-mathematics/discrete-mathematics] Discrete geometry and combinatorial geometry are about combinatorial properties of *discrete collections* of geometrical objects.
[src:discrete-mathematics/discrete-mathematics] A long-standing topic in discrete geometry is tiling of the plane.
[src:discrete-mathematics/discrete-mathematics] In algebraic geometry, the concept of a curve can be extended to discrete geometries by taking the spectra of polynomial rings over finite fields to be models of the affine spaces over that field, and letting subvarieties or spectra of other rings provide the curves that lie in that space.
[src:discrete-mathematics/discrete-mathematics] Although the space in which the curves appear has a finite number of points, the curves are not so much sets of points as analogues of curves in continuous settings.
[src:discrete-mathematics/discrete-mathematics] Algebraic varieties also have a well-defined notion of tangent space called the Zariski tangent space, making many features of calculus applicable even in finite settings.
[src:discrete-mathematics/discrete-mathematics] In applied mathematics, discrete modelling is the discrete analogue of continuous modelling.
[src:discrete-mathematics/discrete-mathematics] In discrete modelling, discrete formulae are fit to data.
[src:discrete-mathematics/discrete-mathematics] A common method in this form of modelling is to use recurrence relation.
[src:discrete-mathematics/discrete-mathematics] Discretization concerns the process of transferring continuous models and equations into discrete counterparts, often for the purposes of making calculations easier by using approximations.
[src:discrete-mathematics/discrete-mathematics] Numerical analysis provides an important example.
[src:discrete-mathematics/discrete-mathematics] The history of discrete mathematics has involved a number of challenging problems which have focused attention within areas of the field.
[src:discrete-mathematics/discrete-mathematics] In graph theory, much research was motivated by attempts to prove the four color theorem, first stated in 1852, but not proved until 1976 (by Kenneth Appel and Wolfgang Haken, using substantial computer assistance).
[src:discrete-mathematics/discrete-mathematics] In logic, the second problem on David Hilbert's list of open problems presented in 1900 was to prove that the axioms of arithmetic are consistent.
[src:discrete-mathematics/discrete-mathematics] Gödel's second incompleteness theorem, proved in 1931, showed that this was not possible – at least not within arithmetic itself.
[src:discrete-mathematics/discrete-mathematics] Hilbert's tenth problem was to determine whether a given polynomial Diophantine equation with integer coefficients has an integer solution.
[src:discrete-mathematics/discrete-mathematics] In 1970, Yuri Matiyasevich proved that this could not be done.
[src:discrete-mathematics/discrete-mathematics] The need to break German codes in World War II led to advances in cryptography and theoretical computer science, with the first programmable digital electronic computer being developed at England's Bletchley Park with the guidance of Alan Turing and his seminal work, On Computable Numbers.
[src:discrete-mathematics/discrete-mathematics] The Cold War meant that cryptography remained important, with fundamental advances such as public-key cryptography being developed in the following decades.
[src:discrete-mathematics/discrete-mathematics] The telecommunications industry has also motivated advances in discrete mathematics, particularly in graph theory and information theory.
[src:discrete-mathematics/discrete-mathematics] Formal verification of statements in logic has been necessary for software development of safety-critical systems, and advances in automated theorem proving have been driven by this need.
[src:discrete-mathematics/discrete-mathematics] Computational geometry has been an important part of the computer graphics incorporated into modern video games and computer-aided design tools.
[src:discrete-mathematics/discrete-mathematics] Several fields of discrete mathematics, particularly theoretical computer science, graph theory, and combinatorics, are important in addressing the challenging bioinformatics problems associated with understanding the tree of life.
[src:discrete-mathematics/discrete-mathematics] Currently, one of the most famous open problems in theoretical computer science is the P = NP problem, which involves the relationship between the complexity classes P and NP.
[src:discrete-mathematics/discrete-mathematics] The Clay Mathematics Institute has offered a $1 million USD prize for the first correct proof, along with prizes for six other mathematical problems.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] In mathematics and computer science, **graph theory** is the study of graphs, which are mathematical structures used to model pairwise relations between objects.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] A graph in this context is made up of vertices (also called nodes or points) which are connected by edges (also called arcs, links, or lines).
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] A distinction is made between undirected graphs, where edges link two vertices symmetrically, and directed graphs, where edges link two vertices asymmetrically.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] Graphs are one of the principal objects of study in discrete mathematics.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] Graph theory is a branch of mathematics that studies graphs, mathematical structures for modelling pairwise relations between objects.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] It is part of discrete mathematics, often considered part of combinatorics, although it is a stand-alone field due to its great growth and distinct from other fields, having its own kind of problems.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] The term "graph" was introduced by James Joseph Sylvester in a paper published in 1878 in *Nature*, where he drew an analogy between "quantic invariants" and "co-variants" of algebra and molecular diagrams.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] The definition of a graph can vary, but one can understand that a graph is a structure consisting of vertices (also called nodes or points) and edges (also called arcs, links, or lines).
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] Two vertices of an edge are called the endpoints.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] Occasionally, a graph is called an undirected graph, to distinguish it from a directed graph.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] A directed graph is a graph where each edge has an assignment direction known as orientation, designated with an arrow.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] A mixed graph can have edges that may be directed, and some may be undirected.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] A graph can also be called a simple graph, to distinguish it from a multigraph.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] A multigraph allows many edges to have the same pair of endpoints, and it also allows an edge to connect a vertex to itself, known as a loop.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] A graph can have its edges assigned a number, which is known as the weight.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] Such a graph is called a weighted graph.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] In 1736, Leonhard Euler published a paper titled *Solutio Problematis ad Geometriam Situs Pertinentis* on the Seven Bridges of Königsberg, which is regarded as the first paper in the history of graph theory.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] Euler's paper and Alexandre-Théophile Vandermonde's 1771 *Remarques sur les Problèmes de Situation* paper on the knight's tour carried on with the *analysis situs*, initiated by Gottfried Wilhelm Leibniz.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] Euler's characteristic relating the number of edges, vertices, and faces of a convex polyhedron was studied and generalized by Augustin-Louis Cauchy and Simon Antoine Jean L'Huilier, and represents the beginning of the branch of mathematics known as topology.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] More than one century after Euler's paper on the bridges of Königsberg, and while Johann Benedict Listing was introducing the concept of topology, Arthur Cayley was led by an interest in particular analytical forms arising from differential calculus to study a particular class of graphs, the trees.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] This study had many implications for theoretical chemistry.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] The techniques he used mainly concern the enumeration of graphs with particular properties.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] Enumerative graph theory then arose from the results of Cayley and the fundamental results published by Pólya between 1935 and 1937.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] These were generalized by Nicolaas Govert de Bruijn in 1959.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] Cayley linked his results on trees with contemporary studies of chemical composition.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] The fusion of ideas from mathematics with those from chemistry began what has become part of the standard terminology of graph theory.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] The autonomous development of topology from 1860 to 1930 fertilized graph theory back through the works of Camille Jordan, Kazimierz Kuratowski, and Hassler Whitney.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] Another important factor in the common development of graph theory and topology came from the use of the techniques of modern algebra.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] The first example of such a use comes from the work of the physicist Gustav Kirchhoff, who published in 1845 his Kirchhoff's circuit laws for calculating the voltage and current in electric circuits.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] The first textbook on graph theory was written by Dénes Kőnig, and published in 1936.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] Another book by Frank Harary, published in 1969, was "considered the world over to be the definitive textbook on the subject", and enabled mathematicians, chemists, electrical engineers and social scientists to talk to each other.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] Harary donated all of the royalties to fund the Pólya Prize.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] One of the most famous problems in graph theory is the four color problem: Is it true that any map drawn in the plane may have its regions colored with four colors, in such a way that any two regions having a common border have different colors?
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] This problem was first posed by Francis Guthrie in 1852, and its first written record is in a letter of Augustus De Morgan addressed to William Rowan Hamilton the same year.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] Many incorrect proofs have been proposed, including those by Augustin Cayley, Alfred Kempe, and others.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] The study and the generalization of this problem by Peter Tait, Percy John Heawood, Frank P.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] Ramsey and Hadwiger led to the study of the colorings of the graphs embedded on surfaces with arbitrary genus.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] Tait's reformulation generated a new class of problems, the *factorization problems*, particularly studied by Petersen and Dénes Kőnig.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] The works of Ramsey on colorations, and more specially, the results obtained by Pál Turán in 1941, were at the origin of another branch of graph theory, known as extremal graph theory.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] The four-color problem remained unsolved for more than a century.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] In 1969, Heinrich Heesch published a method for solving the problem using computers.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] A computer-aided proof produced in 1976 by Kenneth Appel and Wolfgang Haken makes fundamental use of the notion of "discharging" developed by Heesch.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] The proof involved checking the properties of 1,936 configurations by computer, and was not fully accepted at the time due to its complexity.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] A simpler proof considering only 633 configurations was given twenty years later by Robertson, Seymour, Sanders and Thomas.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] The introduction of probabilistic methods in graph theory, especially in the study of Erdős and Rényi of the asymptotic probability of graph connectivity, gave rise to yet another branch, known as random graph theory, which has been a fruitful source of graph-theoretic results.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] Topological graph theory deals with the study of graphs related to topology.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] Topological graph theory deals with the study of graphs as topological spaces.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] The graph in a topology is a set of simplexes that is called the simplicial one-dimensional complex.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] This subarea studies the embedding (or imbedding) of a graph in surface and linkless embedding, graph minors, crossing number, map coloring, and voltage graph.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] The embedding of a graph in a surface is the representation of a graph in which the points are associated with the vertices and simple arcs with edges in a surface.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] The endpoints are associated with an edge, and the points with the end vertices.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] No arcs include points associated with other vertices, and two arcs never intersect at a point that is interior to either of the arcs.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] The graph embedding can be generalized into the linkless embedding, whereby no two cycles of the graph are linked in three-dimensional Euclidean space, and a book, a collection of half-planes all having the same line as their boundary.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] The graph is said to be minor if it can be formed from another graph by deleting vertices and edges, and by edge-contraction.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] The earliest result of the graph minor theory is from Wagner's theorem, stating that a finite graph is planar if and only if its minor includes neither the complete graph on five vertices $K_{5}$ nor the utility graph.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] A related result is the Robertson–Seymour theorem, implying the existence of forbidden minor for every property of graphs preserved by deletions and edge contractions.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] The crossing number tells the minimum number of crossing edges of a graph.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] This study originated from a Hungarian mathematician Pál Turán who asked for a factory plan that minimized the number of crossings between tracks connecting brick kilns to storage sites.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] This problem can be formalized as asking for the crossing number of a complete bipartite graph.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] A graph coloring is a methodical assignment of labelling the elements of a graph, which is traditionally called colors.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] In coloring, no two adjacent elements have the same color.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] It requires the minimum number of colors, which is known as the chromatic number.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] Four-color theorem stated that no more than four colors are required to color the regions of any map so that no two adjacent regions have the same color; that is, no two regions share a common boundary.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] This theorem is stronger than five-color theorem.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] Relatedly, Earth–Moon problem is known for the nowadays open problem on extension of the planar map coloring problem, solved by the four-color theorem.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] A voltage graph is a directed graph whose edges are labelled invertibly by elements of a group.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] This graph concisely specifies the derived graph.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] It is also a common way to form a covering graph.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] Algebraic graph theory is the study of graph theory that involves major branches of algebra.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] Major branches of algebra that are used are linear algebra and group theory.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] A study of graph theory using linear algebra is called spectral graph theory.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] This study focuses on adjacency matrix, a matrix that represents the graph, and its spectrum, which focuses on the characteristic polynomial, eigenvalues, and eigenvectors of the given adjacency matrix.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] It also focuses on the Laplacian matrix of a graph, which involves the degree matrix (a diagonal matrix that represents the degree of a vertex) and the adjacency matrix.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] Group theory, particularly automorphism groups and geometric group theory, focuses on various families of graphs based on symmetry in algebraic graph theory.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] Such a symmetry includes symmetric graphs, vertex-transitive graphs, edge-transitive graphs, distance-transitive graphs, distance-regular graphs, and strongly regular graphs.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] Frucht's theorem states that every finite group is the group of symmetries of a finite undirected graph, or more strongly, there exist infinitely many non-isomorphic simple connected graphs such that the automorphism group of each of them is isomorphic to a finite group.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] Algebraic graph theory also studies the algebraic invariants, chromatic polynomial, Tutte polynomial of a graph, and knot invariant.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] A graph invariant is a property of graphs that depends only on the abstract structure, instead of labellings or drawings of the graph.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] A chromatic polynomial is a polynomial that counts the number of graph colorings as a function of the number of colors.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] The Tutte polynomial is a two-variable polynomial on graph connectivity.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] Geometric graph theory studies a graph drawn with straight-line or continuous curved edges with geometric properties combinatorially.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] Geometric graph theory focuses on combinatorial and geometric properties of a graph that is drawn in a plane with straight-line or continuous curved edges in Euclidean space.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] As part of discrete geometry and computational geometry, geometric graph theory studies planar graphs, relationship to higher-dimensional convex polytopes, intersection of geometrical shaped sets, and other geometries' subareas of incidence geometry and projective geometry.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] A planar graph wherein its vertices are embedded as points, and its edges are non-crossing line segments in the Euclidean plane is called planar straight-line graph.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] Any planar graph can be represented as a planar straight-line graph by Fáry's theorem.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] The planar straight-line graph is the special case of a Euclidean graph.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] The Euclidean graph allows its edges to have the length of the Euclidean distance between its endpoints.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] A visibility graph is a graph whose vertices and edges are the point locations and visible connections, respectively.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] In a simple polygon, where its edges are not self-intersecting and have no holes, the vertices of a visibility graph are connected by edges that represent the sides and diagonals of a polygon.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] The vertices are defined as the point locations.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] Polyhedral graph is an undirected graph that forms the vertices and edges of a three-dimensional convex polyhedron.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] In order to achieve it, such a graph must meet the requirements of Steinitz's theorem, stating that every convex polyhedron is 3-vertex connected planar graph.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] The planar graph remains connected whenever any two of its vertices are removed.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] An intersection graph is a graph in which each vertex is associated with a set and in which vertices are connected by edges whenever the corresponding sets have a nonempty intersection.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] Each vertex is represented as a set, and every two vertices are connected.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] Hence, the intersection graph of finite sets can be represented through the smallest number of required elements, known as the intersection number.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] The result graph can be geometric whenever the sets are geometrical objects.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] For instance, the intersection graph of line segments in one dimension is an interval graph.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] The intersection graph of unit disks in the plane is a unit disk graph.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] The intersection of a circle packing is a coin graph, where a vertex and an edge represent a circle and every pair of tangent circles; by Koebe–Andreev–Thurston theorem, the intersection graphs of non-crossing circles are exactly the planar graphs.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] Scheinerman's theorem states that every planar graph can be represented as the intersection graph of line segments in the plane.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] The Levi graph is a bipartite graph that associates to the incidence structure and projective configuration.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] By applying to information visualization, this creates another subarea of graph theory that is known as graph drawing, which visualizes a graph depiction.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] Frequently drawn as node–link diagrams, the vertices of a graph are represented as disks, boxes, or textual labels, and the edges are represented as line segments, polylines, or curves in the Euclidean plane.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] Many definitions for graph drawings based on quality measures include the crossing number, area, symmetry display on finding the problem of a graph's group automorphism, bend minimization, angular resolution, and slope number.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] Tools for graph drawings are the circle packing, the intersection graph, and other visualizations of the adjacency matrix.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] Extremal graph theory is a branch of mathematics at the intersection of extremal combinatorics and graph theory.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] This area studies the maximum number of a graph's edges, known as the extremal number.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] The subarea's milestone originated from Mantel's theorem on the extremal number of a triangle-free graph.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] Turán's theorem extended Mantel's theorem for any undirected graph that does not have a complete subgraph of a given size.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] Turán's theorem is generalized by Erdős–Stone theorem, which is occasionally known as the "fundamental theorem of extremal graph theory".
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] Extremal graph theory also studies forbidden subgraph problem, homomorphism density, and Szemerédi regularity lemma.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] The forbidden subgraphs problem suggests finding the extremal number of a graph with n vertices such that it does not have a subgraph that is isomorphic to the graph.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] A homomorphism density is a parameter that involves the graph homomorphism.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] The density may refer to the probability that a map from the vertices of a graph to the vertices of another one chosen uniformly at random is a graph homomorphism.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] Being homomorphic means there exists a mapping between two graphs that respects their structure, or equivalently, a function between the vertex sets of two graphs that maps adjacent vertices to adjacent vertices.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] Szemerédi's regularity lemma states that a graph can be partitioned into a bounded number of parts so that the edges between parts are $\varepsilon$ -regular.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] The theory of random graph focuses on graphs using probabilistic method.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] The subarea was founded by Hungarian mathematicians Paul Erdős and Alfréd Rényi, whose modelling generates random graphs, known as Erdős–Rényi model.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] A tree is an undirected graph where every pair of vertices is connected by exactly one path.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] Therefore, a random tree is a tree that is formed by a stochastic process.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] Graphs can be used to model many types of relations and processes in physical, biological, social and information systems.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] Many practical problems can be represented by graphs.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] Emphasizing their application to real-world systems, the term *network* is sometimes defined to mean a graph in which attributes (e.g. names) are associated with the vertices and edges, and the subject that expresses and understands real-world systems as a network is called network science.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] Within computer science, 'causal' and 'non-causal' linked structures are graphs that are used to represent networks of communication, data organization, computational devices, the flow of computation, etc.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] For instance, the link structure of a website can be represented by a directed graph, in which the vertices (nodes) represent web pages and directed edges represent links from one page to another.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] A similar approach can be taken to problems in social media, travel, biology, computer chip design, mapping the progression of neuro-degenerative diseases, and many other fields.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] The development of algorithms to handle graphs is therefore of major interest in computer science.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] The transformation of graphs is often formalized and represented by graph rewrite systems.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] Complementary to graph transformation systems focusing on rule-based in-memory manipulation of graphs are graph databases geared towards transaction-safe, persistent storing and querying of graph-structured data.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] Graph-theoretic methods, in various forms, have proven particularly useful in linguistics, since natural language often lends itself well to discrete structure.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] Traditionally, syntax and compositional semantics follow tree-based structures, whose expressive power lies in the principle of compositionality, modeled in a hierarchical graph.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] More contemporary approaches such as head-driven phrase structure grammar model the syntax of natural language using typed feature structures, which are directed acyclic graphs.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] Within lexical semantics, especially as applied to computers, modeling word meaning is easier when a given word is understood in terms of related words; semantic networks are therefore important in computational linguistics.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] Still, other methods in phonology (e.g. optimality theory, which uses lattice graphs) and morphology (e.g. finite-state morphology, using finite-state transducers) are common in the analysis of language as a graph.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] Indeed, the usefulness of this area of mathematics to linguistics has borne organizations such as TextGraphs, as well as various 'Net' projects, such as WordNet, VerbNet, and others.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] Graph theory is also used to study molecules in chemistry and physics.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] In condensed matter physics, the three-dimensional structure of complicated simulated atomic structures can be studied quantitatively by gathering statistics on graph-theoretic properties related to the topology of the atoms.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] Also, "the Feynman graphs and rules of calculation summarize quantum field theory in a form in close contact with the experimental numbers one wants to understand." In chemistry a graph makes a natural model for a molecule, where vertices represent atoms and edges bonds.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] This approach is especially used in computer processing of molecular structures, ranging from chemical editors to database searching.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] In statistical physics, graphs can represent local connections between interacting parts of a system, as well as the dynamics of a physical process on such systems.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] Similarly, in computational neuroscience graphs can be used to represent functional connections between brain areas that interact to give rise to various cognitive processes, where the vertices represent different areas of the brain and the edges represent the connections between those areas.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] Graph theory plays an important role in electrical modeling of electrical networks, here, weights are associated with resistance of the wire segments to obtain electrical properties of network structures.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] Graphs are also used to represent the micro-scale channels of porous media, in which the vertices represent the pores and the edges represent the smaller channels connecting the pores.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] Chemical graph theory uses the molecular graph as a means to model molecules.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] Graphs and networks are excellent models to study and understand phase transitions and critical phenomena.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] Removal of nodes or edges leads to a critical transition where the network breaks into small clusters which is studied as a phase transition.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] This breakdown is studied via percolation theory.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] Graph theory is also widely used in sociology as a way, for example, to measure actors' prestige or to explore rumor spreading, notably through the use of social network analysis software.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] Under the umbrella of social networks are many different types of graphs.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] Acquaintanceship and friendship graphs describe whether people know each other.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] Influence graphs model whether certain people can influence the behavior of others.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] Finally, collaboration graphs model whether two people work together in a particular way, such as acting in a movie together.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] Likewise, graph theory is useful in biology and conservation efforts where a vertex can represent regions where certain species exist (or inhabit) and the edges represent migration paths or movement between the regions.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] This information is important when looking at breeding patterns or tracking the spread of disease, parasites or how changes to the movement can affect other species.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] Graphs are also commonly used in molecular biology and genomics to model and analyze datasets with complex relationships.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] For example, graph-based methods are often used to 'cluster' cells together into cell-types in single-cell transcriptome analysis.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] Another use is to model genes or proteins in a pathway and study the relationships between them, such as metabolic pathways and gene regulatory networks.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] Evolutionary trees, ecological networks, and hierarchical clustering of gene expression patterns are also represented as graph structures.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] Graph theory is also used in connectomics; nervous systems can be seen as a graph, where the nodes are neurons and the edges are the connections between them.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] A graph structure can be extended by assigning a weight to each edge of the graph.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] Graphs with weights, or weighted graphs, are used to represent structures in which pairwise connections have some numerical values.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] For example, if a graph represents a road network, the weights could represent the length of each road.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] There may be several weights associated with each edge, including distance (as in the previous example), travel time, or monetary cost.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] Such weighted graphs are commonly used to program GPS's, and travel-planning search engines that compare flight times and costs.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] A graph is an abstraction of relationships that emerge in nature; hence, it cannot be coupled to a certain representation.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] The way it is represented depends on the degree of convenience such representation provides for a certain application.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] The most common representations are the visual, in which, usually, vertices are drawn and connected by edges, and the tabular, in which rows of a table provide information about the relationships between the vertices within the graph.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] Graphs are usually represented visually by drawing a point or circle for every vertex, and drawing a line between two vertices if they are connected by an edge.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] If the graph is directed, the direction is indicated by drawing an arrow.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] If the graph is weighted, the weight is added on the arrow.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] A graph drawing should not be confused with the graph itself (the abstract, non-visual structure) as there are several ways to structure the graph drawing.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] All that matters is which vertices are connected to which others by how many edges and not the exact layout.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] In practice, it is often difficult to decide if two drawings represent the same graph.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] Depending on the problem domain some layouts may be better suited and easier to understand than others.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] Tutte was very influential on the subject of graph drawing.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] Among other achievements, he introduced the use of linear algebraic methods to obtain graph drawings.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] Graph drawing also can be said to encompass problems that deal with the crossing number and its various generalizations.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] The crossing number of a graph is the minimum number of intersections between edges that a drawing of the graph in the plane must contain.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] For a planar graph, the crossing number is zero by definition.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] Drawings on surfaces other than the plane are also studied.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] There are other techniques to visualize a graph away from vertices and edges, including circle packings, intersection graph, and other visualizations of the adjacency matrix.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] The tabular representation lends itself well to computational applications.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] There are different ways to store graphs in a computer system.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] The data structure used depends on both the graph structure and the algorithm used for manipulating the graph.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] Theoretically one can distinguish between list and matrix structures but in concrete applications the best structure is often a combination of both.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] List structures are often preferred for sparse graphs as they have smaller memory requirements.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] Matrix structures on the other hand provide faster access for some applications but can consume huge amounts of memory.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] Implementations of sparse matrix structures that are efficient on modern parallel computer architectures are an object of current investigation.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] List structures include the edge list, an array of pairs of vertices, and the adjacency list, which separately lists the neighbors of each vertex: Much like the edge list, each vertex has a list of which vertices it is adjacent to.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] Matrix structures include the incidence matrix, a matrix of 0's and 1's whose rows represent vertices and whose columns represent edges, and the adjacency matrix, in which both the rows and columns are indexed by vertices.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] In both cases a 1 indicates two adjacent objects and a 0 indicates two non-adjacent objects.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] The degree matrix indicates the degree of vertices.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] The Laplacian matrix is a modified form of the adjacency matrix that incorporates information about the degrees of the vertices, and is useful in some calculations such as Kirchhoff's theorem on the number of spanning trees of a graph.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] The distance matrix, like the adjacency matrix, has both its rows and columns indexed by vertices, but rather than containing a 0 or a 1 in each cell it contains the length of a shortest path between two vertices.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] There is a large literature on graphical enumeration: the problem of counting graphs meeting specified conditions.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] Some of this work is found in Harary and Palmer (1973).
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] A common problem, called the subgraph isomorphism problem, is finding a fixed graph as a subgraph in a given graph.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] One reason to be interested in such a question is that many graph properties are *hereditary* for subgraphs, which means that a graph has the property if and only if all subgraphs have it too.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] Finding maximal subgraphs of a certain kind is often an NP-complete problem.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] One special case of subgraph isomorphism is the graph isomorphism problem.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] It asks whether two graphs are isomorphic.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] It is not known whether this problem is NP-complete, nor whether it can be solved in polynomial time.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] A similar problem is finding induced subgraphs in a given graph.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] Again, some important graph properties are hereditary with respect to induced subgraphs, which means that a graph has a property if and only if all induced subgraphs also have it.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] Finding maximal induced subgraphs of a certain kind is also often NP-complete.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] Still another such problem, the minor containment problem, is to find a fixed graph as a minor of a given graph.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] A minor or subcontraction of a graph is any graph obtained by taking a subgraph and contracting some (or no) edges.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] Many graph properties are hereditary for minors, which means that a graph has a property if and only if all minors have it too.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] A similar problem, the subdivision containment problem, is to find a fixed graph as a subdivision of a given graph.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] A subdivision or homeomorphism of a graph is any graph obtained by subdividing some (or no) edges.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] Subdivision containment is related to graph properties such as planarity.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] Another class of problems has to do with the extent to which various species and generalizations of graphs are determined by their *point-deleted subgraphs*.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] Many problems and theorems in graph theory have to do with various ways of coloring graphs.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] Typically, one is interested in coloring a graph so that no two adjacent vertices have the same color, or with other similar restrictions.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] One may also consider coloring edges (possibly so that no two coincident edges are the same color), or other variations.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] Constraint modeling theories concern families of directed graphs related by a partial order.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] In these applications, graphs are ordered by specificity, meaning that more constrained graphs—which are more specific and thus contain a greater amount of information—are subsumed by those that are more general.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] Operations between graphs include evaluating the direction of a subsumption relationship between two graphs, if any, and computing graph unification.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] The unification of two argument graphs is defined as the most general graph (or the computation thereof) that is consistent with (i.e. contains all of the information in) the inputs, if such a graph exists; efficient unification algorithms are known.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] For constraint frameworks which are strictly compositional, graph unification is the sufficient satisfiability and combination function.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] Well-known applications include automatic theorem proving and modeling the elaboration of linguistic structure.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] Covering problems in graphs may refer to various set cover problems on subsets of vertices/subgraphs.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] Decomposition, defined as partitioning the edge set of a graph (with as many vertices as necessary accompanying the edges of each part of the partition), has a wide variety of questions.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] Often, the problem is to decompose a graph into subgraphs isomorphic to a fixed graph; for instance, decomposing a complete graph into Hamiltonian cycles.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] Other problems specify a family of graphs into which a given graph should be decomposed, for instance, a family of cycles, or decomposing a complete graph *K**n* into *n* − 1 specified trees having, respectively, 1, 2, 3, ..., *n* − 1 edges.
[src:discrete-mathematics/graph-theory] Many problems involve characterizing the members of various classes of graphs.
[src:discrete-mathematics/mathematical-induction] — *Concrete Mathematics*, page 3 margins.
[src:discrete-mathematics/mathematical-induction] A **proof by induction** consists of two cases.
[src:discrete-mathematics/mathematical-induction] The first, the **base case**, proves the statement for $n=0$ without assuming any knowledge of other cases.
[src:discrete-mathematics/mathematical-induction] The second case, the **induction step**, proves that *if* the statement holds for any given case $n=k$ , *then* it must also hold for the next case $n=k+1$ .
[src:discrete-mathematics/mathematical-induction] These two steps establish that the statement holds for every natural number n .
[src:discrete-mathematics/mathematical-induction] The base case does not necessarily begin with $n=0$ , but often with $n=1$ , and possibly with any fixed natural number $n=N$ , establishing the truth of the statement for all natural numbers $n\geq N$ .
[src:discrete-mathematics/mathematical-induction] The method can be extended to prove statements about more general well-founded structures, such as trees; this generalization, known as structural induction, is used in mathematical logic and computer science.
[src:discrete-mathematics/mathematical-induction] Mathematical induction in this extended sense is closely related to recursion.
[src:discrete-mathematics/mathematical-induction] Mathematical induction is an inference rule used in formal proofs, and is the foundation of most correctness proofs for computer programs.
[src:discrete-mathematics/mathematical-induction] Despite its name, mathematical induction differs fundamentally from inductive reasoning as used in philosophy, in which the examination of many cases results in a probable conclusion.
[src:discrete-mathematics/mathematical-induction] The mathematical method examines infinitely many cases to prove a general statement, but it does so by a finite chain of deductive reasoning involving the variable n , which can take infinitely many values.
[src:discrete-mathematics/mathematical-induction] The result is a rigorous proof of the statement, not an assertion of its probability.
[src:discrete-mathematics/mathematical-induction] Joyce, there is no evidence for the use of the principle of mathematical induction in Euclid’s writings.
[src:discrete-mathematics/mathematical-induction] Acerbi (2000) argues that Plato’s *Parmenides* (c.
[src:discrete-mathematics/mathematical-induction] 370 BC) contains traces of an early implicit inductive proof.
[src:discrete-mathematics/mathematical-induction] This interpretation has been challenged by Negrepontis and Farmaki (2021), who further state that neither Plato nor any of the other Pythagoreans used the principle of mathematical induction.
[src:discrete-mathematics/mathematical-induction] The earliest implicit proof by mathematical induction was written by al-Karaji around 1000 AD, who applied it to arithmetic sequences to prove the binomial theorem and properties of Pascal's triangle.
[src:discrete-mathematics/mathematical-induction] Whilst the original work was lost, it was later referenced by Al-Samawal al-Maghribi in his treatise *al-Bahir fi'l-jabr (The Brilliant in Algebra)* in around 1150 AD.
[src:discrete-mathematics/mathematical-induction] In India, early implicit proofs by mathematical induction appear in Bhaskara's "cyclic method".
[src:discrete-mathematics/mathematical-induction] None of these ancient mathematicians, however, explicitly stated the induction hypothesis.
[src:discrete-mathematics/mathematical-induction] Another similar case (contrary to what Vacca has written, as Freudenthal carefully showed) was that of Francesco Maurolico in his *Arithmeticorum libri duo* (1575), who used the technique to prove that the sum of the first n odd integers is *n*2.
[src:discrete-mathematics/mathematical-induction] The earliest rigorous use of induction was by Gersonides (1288–1344).
[src:discrete-mathematics/mathematical-induction] The first explicit formulation of the principle of induction was given by Pascal in his *Traité du triangle arithmétique* (1665).
[src:discrete-mathematics/mathematical-induction] Another Frenchman, Fermat, made ample use of a related principle: indirect proof by infinite descent.
[src:discrete-mathematics/mathematical-induction] The induction hypothesis was also employed by the Swiss Jakob Bernoulli, and from then on it became well known.
[src:discrete-mathematics/mathematical-induction] The modern formal treatment of the principle came only in the 19th century, with George Boole, Augustus De Morgan, Charles Sanders Peirce, Giuseppe Peano, and Richard Dedekind.
[src:discrete-mathematics/mathematical-induction] The simplest and most common form of mathematical induction infers that a statement involving a natural number n (that is, an integer *n* ≥ 0 or 1) holds for all values of n.
[src:discrete-mathematics/mathematical-induction] The **induction step** (or **inductive step**, or **step case**): prove that for every n, if the statement holds for n, then it holds for *n* + 1.
[src:discrete-mathematics/mathematical-induction] In other words, assume that the statement holds for some arbitrary natural number n, and prove that the statement holds for *n* + 1.
[src:discrete-mathematics/mathematical-induction] The hypothesis in the induction step, that the statement holds for a particular n, is called the **induction hypothesis** or **inductive hypothesis**.
[src:discrete-mathematics/mathematical-induction] To prove the induction step, one assumes the induction hypothesis for n and then uses this assumption to prove that the statement holds for *n* + 1.
[src:discrete-mathematics/mathematical-induction] Authors who prefer to define natural numbers to begin at 0 use that value in the base case; those who define natural numbers to begin at 1 use that value.
[src:discrete-mathematics/mathematical-induction] Equating the extreme left hand and right hand sides, we deduce that: $0+1+2+\cdots +k+(k+1)={\frac {(k+1)((k+1)+1)}{2}}.$ That is, the statement $P(k+1)$ also holds true, establishing the induction step.
[src:discrete-mathematics/mathematical-induction] Induction is often used to prove inequalities.
[src:discrete-mathematics/mathematical-induction] As an example, we prove that $\left|\sin nx\right|\leq n\left|\sin x\right|$ for any real number x and natural number n .
[src:discrete-mathematics/mathematical-induction] At first glance, it may appear that a more general version, $\left|\sin nx\right|\leq n\left|\sin x\right|$ for any *real* numbers $n,x$ , could be proven without induction; but the case ${\textstyle n={\frac {1}{2}},\,x=\pi }$ shows it may be false for non-integer values of n .
[src:discrete-mathematics/mathematical-induction] This suggests we examine the statement specifically for *natural* values of n , and induction is the readiest tool.
[src:discrete-mathematics/mathematical-induction] The inequality between the extreme left-hand and right-hand quantities shows that $P(k+1)$ is true, which completes the induction step.
[src:discrete-mathematics/mathematical-induction] In practice, proofs by induction are often structured differently, depending on the exact nature of the property to be proven.
[src:discrete-mathematics/mathematical-induction] All variants of induction are special cases of transfinite induction; see below.
[src:discrete-mathematics/mathematical-induction] Showing that if the statement holds for an arbitrary number *n* ≥ *b*, then the same statement also holds for *n* + 1.
[src:discrete-mathematics/mathematical-induction] This can be used, for example, to show that 2*n* ≥ *n* + 5 for *n* ≥ 3.
[src:discrete-mathematics/mathematical-induction] In this way, one can prove that some statement *P*(*n*) holds for all *n* ≥ 1, or even for all *n* ≥ −5.
[src:discrete-mathematics/mathematical-induction] This form of mathematical induction is actually a special case of the previous form, because if the statement to be proved is *P*(*n*) then proving it with these two rules is equivalent with proving *P*(*n* + *b*) for all natural numbers n with an induction base case 0.
[src:discrete-mathematics/mathematical-induction] Assume an infinite supply of 4- and 5-dollar coins.
[src:discrete-mathematics/mathematical-induction] Induction can be used to prove that any whole amount of dollars greater than or equal to 12 can be formed by a combination of such coins.
[src:discrete-mathematics/mathematical-induction] Let *S*(*k*) denote the statement "k dollars can be formed by a combination of 4- and 5-dollar coins".
[src:discrete-mathematics/mathematical-induction] Therefore, by the principle of induction, *S*(*k*) holds for all *k* ≥ 12, and the proof is complete.
[src:discrete-mathematics/mathematical-induction] In this example, although *S*(*k*) also holds for ${\textstyle k\in \{4,5,8,9,10\}}$ , the above proof cannot be modified to replace the minimum amount of 12 dollar to any lower value m.
[src:discrete-mathematics/mathematical-induction] For *m* = 11, the base case is actually false; for *m* = 10, the second case in the induction step (replacing three 5- by four 4-dollar coins) will not work; let alone for even lower m.
[src:discrete-mathematics/mathematical-induction] It is sometimes desirable to prove a statement involving two natural numbers, n and m, by iterating the induction process.
[src:discrete-mathematics/mathematical-induction] That is, one proves a base case and an induction step for n, and in each of those proves a base case and an induction step for m.
[src:discrete-mathematics/mathematical-induction] See, for example, the proof of commutativity accompanying *addition of natural numbers*.
[src:discrete-mathematics/mathematical-induction] More complicated arguments involving three or more counters are also possible.
[src:discrete-mathematics/mathematical-induction] The method of infinite descent is a variation of mathematical induction which was used by Pierre de Fermat.
[src:discrete-mathematics/mathematical-induction] It is used to show that some statement *Q*(*n*) is false for all natural numbers n.
[src:discrete-mathematics/mathematical-induction] Its traditional form consists of showing that if *Q*(*n*) is true for some natural number n, it also holds for some strictly smaller natural number m.
[src:discrete-mathematics/mathematical-induction] Because there are no infinite decreasing sequences of natural numbers, this situation would be impossible, thereby showing (by contradiction) that *Q*(*n*) cannot be true for any n.
[src:discrete-mathematics/mathematical-induction] The validity of this method can be verified from the usual principle of mathematical induction.
[src:discrete-mathematics/mathematical-induction] Using mathematical induction on the statement *P*(*n*) defined as "*Q*(*m*) is false for all natural numbers m less than or equal to n", it follows that *P*(*n*) holds for all n, which means that *Q*(*n*) is false for every natural number n.
[src:discrete-mathematics/mathematical-induction] whereupon the induction principle "automates" n applications of this step in getting from *P*(0) to *P*(*n*).
[src:discrete-mathematics/mathematical-induction] This could be called "predecessor induction" because each step proves something about a number from something about that number's predecessor.
[src:discrete-mathematics/mathematical-induction] The induction principle then "automates" log2 *n* applications of this inference in getting from *P*(0) to *P*(*n*).
[src:discrete-mathematics/mathematical-induction] In fact, it is called "prefix induction" because each step proves something about a number from something about the "prefix" of that number — as formed by truncating the low bit of its binary representation.
[src:discrete-mathematics/mathematical-induction] It can also be viewed as an application of traditional induction on the length of that binary representation.
[src:discrete-mathematics/mathematical-induction] If traditional predecessor induction is interpreted computationally as an n-step loop, then prefix induction would correspond to a log-n-step loop.
[src:discrete-mathematics/mathematical-induction] Because of that, proofs using prefix induction are "more feasibly constructive" than proofs using predecessor induction.
[src:discrete-mathematics/mathematical-induction] Predecessor induction can trivially simulate prefix induction on the same statement.
[src:discrete-mathematics/mathematical-induction] One can take the idea a step further: one must prove $\forall k\,\left(P\!\left(\left\lfloor {\sqrt {k}}\right\rfloor \right)\to P(k)\right)$ whereupon the induction principle "automates" log log *n* applications of this inference in getting from *P*(0) to *P*(*n*).
[src:discrete-mathematics/mathematical-induction] This form of induction has been used, analogously, to study log-time parallel computation.
[src:discrete-mathematics/mathematical-induction] The name "strong induction" does not mean that this method can prove more than "weak induction", but merely refers to the stronger hypothesis used in the induction step.
[src:discrete-mathematics/mathematical-induction] In fact, it can be shown that the two methods are actually equivalent, as explained below.
[src:discrete-mathematics/mathematical-induction] In this form of complete induction, one still has to prove the base case, $P(0)$ , and it may even be necessary to prove extra-base cases such as $P(1)$ before the general argument applies, as in the example below of the Fibonacci number $F_{n}$ .
[src:discrete-mathematics/mathematical-induction] Although the form just described requires one to prove the base case, this is unnecessary if one can prove $P(m)$ (assuming $P(n)$ for all lower n ) for all $m\geq 0$ .
[src:discrete-mathematics/mathematical-induction] This is a special case of transfinite induction as described below, although it is no longer equivalent to ordinary induction.
[src:discrete-mathematics/mathematical-induction] In this form the base case is subsumed by the case $m=0$ , where $P(0)$ is proved with no other $P(n)$ assumed; this case may need to be handled separately, but sometimes the same argument applies for $m=0$ and $m>0$ , making the proof simpler and more elegant.
[src:discrete-mathematics/mathematical-induction] In this method, however, it is vital to ensure that the proof of $P(m)$ does not implicitly assume that $m>0$ , e.g. by saying "choose an arbitrary $n<m$ ", or by assuming that a set of m elements has an element.
[src:discrete-mathematics/mathematical-induction] Complete induction is equivalent to ordinary mathematical induction as described above, in the sense that a proof by one method can be transformed into a proof by the other.
[src:discrete-mathematics/mathematical-induction] Suppose there is a proof of $P(n)$ by complete induction.
[src:discrete-mathematics/mathematical-induction] Then, this proof can be transformed into an ordinary induction proof by assuming a stronger inductive hypothesis.
[src:discrete-mathematics/mathematical-induction] Let $Q(n)$ be the statement " $P(m)$ holds for all m such that $0\leq m\leq n$ "—this becomes the inductive hypothesis for ordinary induction.
[src:discrete-mathematics/mathematical-induction] We can then show $Q(0)$ and $Q(n+1)$ for $n\in \mathbb {N}$ assuming only $Q(n)$ and show that $Q(n)$ implies $P(n)$ .
[src:discrete-mathematics/mathematical-induction] Complete induction is most useful when several instances of the inductive hypothesis are required for each induction step.
[src:discrete-mathematics/mathematical-induction] By using the fact that $F_{n+2}=F_{n+1}+F_{n}$ for each $n\in \mathbb {N}$ , the identity above can be verified by direct calculation for ${\textstyle F_{n+2}}$ if one assumes that it already holds for both ${\textstyle F_{n+1}}$ and ${\textstyle F_{n}}$ .
[src:discrete-mathematics/mathematical-induction] To complete the proof, the identity must be verified in the two base cases: $n=0$ and ${\textstyle n=1}$ .
[src:discrete-mathematics/mathematical-induction] Another proof by complete induction uses the hypothesis that the statement holds for *all* smaller n more thoroughly.
[src:discrete-mathematics/mathematical-induction] Consider the statement that "every natural number greater than 1 is a product of (one or more) prime numbers", which is the "existence" part of the fundamental theorem of arithmetic.
[src:discrete-mathematics/mathematical-induction] For proving the induction step, the induction hypothesis is that for a given $m>1$ the statement holds for all smaller $n>1$ .
[src:discrete-mathematics/mathematical-induction] If m is prime then it is certainly a product of primes, and if not, then by definition it is a product: $m=n_{1}n_{2}$ , where neither of the factors is equal to 1; hence neither is equal to m , and so both are greater than 1 and smaller than m .
[src:discrete-mathematics/mathematical-induction] The induction hypothesis now applies to $n_{1}$ and $n_{2}$ , so each one is a product of primes.
[src:discrete-mathematics/mathematical-induction] Thus m is a product of products of primes, and hence by extension a product of primes itself.
[src:discrete-mathematics/mathematical-induction] We shall look to prove the same example as above, this time with *strong induction*.
[src:discrete-mathematics/mathematical-induction] However, there will be slight differences in the structure and the assumptions of the proof, starting with the extended base case.
[src:discrete-mathematics/mathematical-induction] Choosing $m=j-4$ , and observing that $15<j\implies 12\leq j-4<j$ shows that $S(j-4)$ holds, by the inductive hypothesis.
[src:discrete-mathematics/mathematical-induction] That is, the sum $j-4$ can be formed by some combination of 4 and 5 dollar coins.
[src:discrete-mathematics/mathematical-induction] Then, simply adding a 4 dollar coin to that combination yields the sum j .
[src:discrete-mathematics/mathematical-induction] Sometimes, it is more convenient to deduce backwards, proving the statement for $n-1$ , given its validity for n .
[src:discrete-mathematics/mathematical-induction] However, proving the validity of the statement for no single number suffices to establish the base case; instead, one needs to prove the statement for an infinite subset of the natural numbers.
[src:discrete-mathematics/mathematical-induction] For example, Augustin Louis Cauchy first used forward (regular) induction to prove the inequality of arithmetic and geometric means for all powers of 2, and then used backwards induction to show it for all natural numbers.
[src:discrete-mathematics/mathematical-induction] The induction step must be proved for all values of n.
[src:discrete-mathematics/mathematical-induction] The base case $n=1$ is trivial, and the induction step is correct in all cases $n>1$ .
[src:discrete-mathematics/mathematical-induction] However, the argument used in the induction step is incorrect for $n+1=2$ , because the statement that "the two sets overlap" is false for ${\textstyle \left\{1\right\}}$ and ${\textstyle \left\{2\right\}}$ .
[src:discrete-mathematics/mathematical-induction] In words, the base case *P*(0) and the induction step (namely, that the induction hypothesis *P*(*k*) implies *P*(*k* + 1)) together imply that *P*(*n*) for any natural number n.
[src:discrete-mathematics/mathematical-induction] The axiom of induction asserts the validity of inferring that *P*(*n*) holds for any natural number n from the base case and the induction step.
[src:discrete-mathematics/mathematical-induction] The first quantifier in the axiom ranges over *predicates* rather than over individual numbers.
[src:discrete-mathematics/mathematical-induction] This is a second-order quantifier, which means that this axiom is stated in second-order logic.
[src:discrete-mathematics/mathematical-induction] Axiomatizing arithmetic induction in first-order logic requires an axiom schema containing a separate axiom for each possible predicate.
[src:discrete-mathematics/mathematical-induction] The article Peano axioms contains further discussion of this issue.
[src:discrete-mathematics/mathematical-induction] The successor function s of every natural number yields a natural number (*s*(*x*) = *x* + 1).
[src:discrete-mathematics/mathematical-induction] This is not an axiom, but a theorem, given that natural numbers are defined in the language of ZFC set theory by axioms, analogous to Peano's.
[src:discrete-mathematics/mathematical-induction] See construction of the natural numbers using the axiom of infinity and axiom schema of specification.
[src:discrete-mathematics/mathematical-induction] One variation of the principle of complete induction can be generalized for statements about elements of any well-founded set, that is, a set with an irreflexive relation < that contains no infinite descending chains.
[src:discrete-mathematics/mathematical-induction] Every set representing an ordinal number is well-founded, the set of natural numbers is one of them.
[src:discrete-mathematics/mathematical-induction] Applied to a well-founded set, transfinite induction can be formulated as a single step.
[src:discrete-mathematics/mathematical-induction] This form of induction, when applied to a set of ordinal numbers (which form a well-ordered and hence well-founded class), is called *transfinite induction*.
[src:discrete-mathematics/mathematical-induction] It is an important proof technique in set theory, topology and other fields.
[src:discrete-mathematics/mathematical-induction] 3. when n has no direct predecessor, i.e. n is a so-called limit ordinal.
[src:discrete-mathematics/mathematical-induction] Strictly speaking, it is not necessary in transfinite induction to prove a base case, because it is a vacuous special case of the proposition that if *P* is true of all *n* < *m*, then *P* is true of m.
[src:discrete-mathematics/mathematical-induction] It is vacuously true precisely because there are no values of *n* < *m* that could serve as counterexamples.
[src:discrete-mathematics/mathematical-induction] So the special cases are special cases of the general case.
[src:discrete-mathematics/mathematical-induction] The principle of mathematical induction is usually stated as an axiom of the natural numbers; see Peano axioms.
[src:discrete-mathematics/mathematical-induction] It is strictly stronger than the well-ordering principle in the context of the other Peano axioms.
[src:discrete-mathematics/mathematical-induction] It can then be proved that induction, given the above-listed axioms, implies the well-ordering principle.
[src:discrete-mathematics/mathematical-induction] The following proof uses complete induction and the first and fourth axioms.
[src:discrete-mathematics/mathematical-induction] On the other hand, the set $\{(0,n):n\in \mathbb {N} \}\cup \{(1,n):n\in \mathbb {N} \}$ , shown in the picture, is well-ordered by the lexicographic order.
[src:discrete-mathematics/mathematical-induction] Moreover, except for the induction axiom, it satisfies all Peano axioms, where Peano's constant 0 is interpreted as the pair (0, 0), and Peano's *successor* function is defined on pairs by succ(*x*, *n*) = (*x*, *n* + 1) for all $x\in \{0,1\}$ and $n\in \mathbb {N}$ .
[src:discrete-mathematics/mathematical-induction] Then the base case *P*(0, 0) is trivially true, and so is the induction step: if *P*(*x*, *n*), then *P*(succ(*x*, *n*)).
[src:discrete-mathematics/mathematical-induction] However, *P* is not true for all pairs in the set, since *P*(1,0) is false.
[src:discrete-mathematics/mathematical-induction] Peano's axioms with the induction principle uniquely model the natural numbers.
[src:discrete-mathematics/mathematical-induction] Replacing the induction principle with the well-ordering principle allows for more exotic models that fulfill all the axioms.
[src:discrete-mathematics/mathematical-induction] It is mistakenly printed in several books and sources that the well-ordering principle is equivalent to the induction axiom.
[src:discrete-mathematics/mathematical-induction] A common mistake in many erroneous proofs is to assume that *n* − 1 is a unique and well-defined natural number, a property which is not implied by the other Peano axioms.
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p01] Anagrams of a word whose letters are all different are also permutations: the letters are already ordered in the original word, and the anagram reorders them.
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p01] The study of permutations of finite sets is an important topic in combinatorics and group theory.
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p01] Permutations are used in almost every branch of mathematics and in many other fields of science.
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p01] In computer science, they are used for analyzing sorting algorithms; in quantum physics, for describing states of particles; and in biology, for describing RNA sequences.
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p01] The number of permutations of *n* distinct objects is *n* factorial, usually written as *n*!, which means the product of all positive integers less than or equal to *n*.
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p01] According to the second meaning, a permutation of a set *S* is defined as a bijection from *S* to itself.
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p01] That is, it is a function from *S* to *S* for which every element occurs exactly once as an image value.
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p01] Such a function $\sigma :S\to S$ is equivalent to the rearrangement of the elements of *S* in which each element *i* is replaced by the corresponding $\sigma (i)$ .
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p01] For example, the permutation (3, 1, 2) corresponds to the function $\sigma$ defined as $\sigma (1)=3,\quad \sigma (2)=1,\quad \sigma (3)=2.$ The collection of all permutations of a set form a group called the symmetric group of the set.
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p01] The group operation is the composition of functions (performing one rearrangement after the other), which results in another function (rearrangement).
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p01] In elementary combinatorics, the ***k*-permutations**, or partial permutations, are the ordered arrangements of *k* distinct elements selected from a set.
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p01] When *k* is equal to the size of the set, these are the permutations in the previous sense.
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p01] Permutation-like objects called hexagrams were used in China in the I Ching (Pinyin: Yi Jing) as early as 1000 BC.
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p01] In Greece, Plutarch wrote that Xenocrates of Chalcedon (396–314 BC) discovered the number of different syllables possible in the Greek language.
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p01] This would have been the first attempt on record to solve a difficult problem in permutations and combinations.
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p01] Al-Khalil (717–786), an Arab mathematician and cryptographer, wrote the *Book of Cryptographic Messages*.
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p01] It contains the first use of permutations and combinations, to list all possible Arabic words with and without vowels.
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p01] The rule to determine the number of permutations of *n* objects was known in Indian culture around 1150 AD.
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p01] In 1677, Fabian Stedman described factorials when explaining the number of permutations of bells in change ringing.
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p01] Starting from two bells: "first, *two* must be admitted to be varied in two ways", which he illustrates by showing 1 2 and 2 1.
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p01] He then explains that with three bells there are "three times two figures to be produced out of three" which again is illustrated.
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p01] His explanation involves "cast away 3, and 1.2 will remain; cast away 2, and 1.3 will remain; cast away 1, and 2.3 will remain".
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p01] He then moves on to four bells and repeats the casting away argument showing that there will be four different sets of three.
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p01] Effectively, this is a recursive process.
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p01] He continues with five bells using the "casting away" method and tabulates the resulting 120 combinations.
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p01] Stedman widens the consideration of permutations; he goes on to consider the number of permutations of the letters of the alphabet and of horses from a stable of 20.
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p01] This line of work ultimately resulted, through the work of Évariste Galois, in Galois theory, which gives a complete description of what is possible and impossible with respect to solving polynomial equations (in one unknown) by radicals.
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p01] In modern mathematics, there are many similar situations in which understanding a problem requires studying certain permutations related to it.
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p01] The study of permutations as substitutions on n elements led to the notion of group as algebraic structure, through the works of Cauchy (1815 memoir).
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p01] Permutations played an important role in the cryptanalysis of the Enigma machine, a cipher device used by Nazi Germany during World War II.
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p01] In particular, one important property of permutations, namely, that two permutations are conjugate exactly when they have the same cycle type, was used by cryptologist Marian Rejewski to break the German Enigma cipher in turn of years 1932–1933.
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p01] In mathematics texts it is customary to denote permutations using lowercase Greek letters.
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p01] The set of all permutations of a set with *n* elements forms the symmetric group $S_{n}$ , where the group operation is composition of functions.
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p01] Thus for two permutations $\sigma$ and $\tau$ in the group $S_{n}$ , their product $\pi =\sigma \tau$ is defined by $\pi (i)=\sigma (\tau (i)).$ Composition is usually written without a dot or other sign.
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p01] In general, composition of two permutations is not commutative; that is, typically the permutations $\tau \sigma$ and $\sigma \tau$ are not equal.
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p01] As a bijection from a set to itself, a permutation is a function that *performs* a rearrangement of a set, termed an *active permutation* or *substitution*.
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p01] An older viewpoint sees a permutation as an ordered arrangement or list of all the elements of *S*, called a *passive permutation*.
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p01] According to this definition, all permutations in § One-line notation are passive.
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p01] This meaning is subtly distinct from how passive (i.e.
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p01] *alias*) is used in Active and passive transformation and elsewhere, which would consider all permutations open to passive interpretation (regardless of whether they are in one-line notation, two-line notation, etc.).
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p01] A permutation $\sigma$ can be decomposed into one or more disjoint *cycles* which are the orbits of the cyclic group $\langle \sigma \rangle =\{1,\sigma ,\sigma ^{2},\ldots \}$ acting on the set *S*.
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p01] A cycle is found by repeatedly applying the permutation to an element: $x,\sigma (x),\sigma (\sigma (x)),\ldots ,\sigma ^{k-1}(x)$ , where we assume $\sigma ^{k}(x)=x$ .
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p01] A cycle consisting of *k* elements is called a *k*-cycle.
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p01] A fixed point of a permutation $\sigma$ is an element *x* which is taken to itself, that is $\sigma (x)=x$ , forming a 1-cycle $(\,x\,)$ .
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p01] A permutation with no fixed points is called a derangement.
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p01] A permutation exchanging two elements (a single 2-cycle) and leaving the others fixed is called a transposition.
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p01] Several notations are widely used to represent permutations conveniently.
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p01] The properties of permutations do not depend on the nature of the elements being permuted, only on their number, so one often considers the standard set $\{1,2,\ldots ,n\}$ .
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p01] *Cycle notation* is a popular choice, as it is compact and shows the permutation's structure clearly.
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p01] This article will use cycle notation unless otherwise specified.
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p01] Cauchy's *two-line notation* lists the elements of *S* in the first row, and the image of each element below it in the second row.
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p01] that is, as an ordered arrangement of the elements of *S*.
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p01] Care must be taken to distinguish one-line notation from the cycle notation described below: a common usage is to omit parentheses or other enclosing marks for one-line notation, while using parentheses for cycle notation.
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p01] The one-line notation is also called the *word representation*.
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p01] This compact form is common in elementary combinatorics and computer science.
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p01] It is especially useful in applications where the permutations are to be compared as larger or smaller using lexicographic order.
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p01] Cycle notation describes the effect of repeatedly applying the permutation on the elements of the set *S*, with an orbit being called a *cycle*.
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p01] The permutation is written as a list of cycles; since distinct cycles involve disjoint sets of elements, this is referred to as "decomposition into disjoint cycles".
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p01] Repeat until all elements of *S* are written in cycles.
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p01] Also, it is common to omit 1-cycles, since these can be inferred: for any element *x* in *S* not appearing in any cycle, one implicitly assumes $\sigma (x)=x$ .
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p01] Following the convention of omitting 1-cycles, one may interpret an individual cycle as a permutation which fixes all the elements not in the cycle (a cyclic permutation having only one cycle of length greater than 1).
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p01] Then the list of disjoint cycles can be seen as the composition of these cyclic permutations.
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p01] A convenient feature of cycle notation is that inverting the permutation is given by reversing the order of the elements in each cycle.
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p01] Any permutation has a particular choice of cycle notation which is useful in many combinatorial contexts, especially Foata's bijection described below.
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p01] Richard Stanley calls this the *standard representation*, and Martin Aigner uses *standard form*.
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p01] Sergey Kitaev also uses the "standard form" terminology, but reverses both choices; that is, each cycle lists its minimal element first, and the cycles are sorted in decreasing order of their minimal elements.
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p01] There are two ways to denote the composition of two permutations.
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p01] In the most common notation, $\sigma \cdot \tau$ is the function that maps any element *x* to $\sigma (\tau (x))$ .
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p01] The rightmost permutation is applied to the argument first, because the argument is written to the right of the function.
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p01] A *different* rule for multiplying permutations comes from writing the argument to the left of the function, so that the leftmost permutation acts first.
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p01] In this notation, the permutation is often written as an exponent, so *σ* acting on *x* is written *x**σ*; then the product is defined by $x^{\sigma \cdot \tau }=(x^{\sigma })^{\tau }$ .
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p01] This article uses the first definition, where the rightmost permutation is applied first.
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p01] The function composition operation satisfies the axioms of a group.
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p01] It is associative, meaning $(\rho \sigma )\tau =\rho (\sigma \tau )$ , and products of more than two permutations are usually written without parentheses.
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p01] The composition operation also has an identity element (the identity permutation ${\text{id}}$ ), and each permutation $\sigma$ has an inverse $\sigma ^{-1}$ (its inverse function) with $\sigma ^{-1}\sigma =\sigma \sigma ^{-1}={\text{id}}$ .
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p01] The concept of a permutation as an ordered arrangement admits several generalizations that have been called *permutations*, especially in older literature.
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p01] In older literature and elementary textbooks, a ***k*-permutation of *n*** (sometimes called a **partial permutation**, **sequence without repetition**, **variation**, or **arrangement**) means an ordered arrangement (list) of a *k*-element subset of an *n*-set.
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p01] This usage of the term *permutation* is closely associated with the term *combination* to mean a subset: that is, a *k-combination* of a set *S* is a *k-*element (unordered) subset of *S*.
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p01] Ordering the *k*-combinations of *S* in all possible ways produces the *k*-permutations of *S*.
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p01] Ordered arrangements of *k* elements of a set *S*, where repetition is allowed, are called *k*-tuples.
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p01] They have sometimes been referred to as **permutations with repetition**, although they are not permutations in the usual sense.
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p01] They are also called words or strings over the alphabet *S*.
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p01] If *M* is a finite multiset, then a **multiset permutation** is an ordered arrangement of elements of *M* in which each element appears a number of times equal exactly to its multiplicity in *M*.
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p01] An anagram of a word having some repeated letters is an example of a multiset permutation.
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p01] A ***k*-permutation** of a multiset *M* is a sequence of *k* elements of *M* in which each element appears *a number of times less than or equal to* its multiplicity in *M* (an element's *repetition number*).
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p01] Permutations, when considered as arrangements, are sometimes referred to as *linearly ordered* arrangements.
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p01] If, however, the objects are arranged in a circular manner this distinguished ordering is weakened: there is no "first element" in the arrangement, as any element can be considered as the start.
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p01] An arrangement of distinct objects in a circular manner is called a **circular permutation**.
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p01] These can be formally defined as equivalence classes of ordinary permutations of these objects, for the equivalence relation generated by moving the final element of the linear arrangement to its front.
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p01] Two circular permutations are equivalent if one can be rotated into the other.
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p01] The following four circular permutations on four letters are considered to be the same.
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p01] The circular arrangements are to be read counter-clockwise, so the following two are not equivalent since no rotation can bring one to the other.
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p01] There are (*n* – 1)! circular permutations of a set with *n* elements.
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p01] The number of permutations of *n* distinct objects is *n*!.
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p01] The number of *n*-permutations with *k* disjoint cycles is the signless Stirling number of the first kind, denoted $c(n,k)$ or $[{\begin{smallmatrix}n\\k\end{smallmatrix}}]$ .
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p01] The cycles (including the fixed points) of a permutation $\sigma$ of a set with n elements partition that set; so the lengths of these cycles form an integer partition of n, which is called the **cycle type** (or sometimes **cycle structure** or **cycle shape**) of $\sigma$ .
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p01] There is a "1" in the cycle type for every fixed point of $\sigma$ , a "2" for every transposition, and so on.
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p01] This may also be written in a more compact form as [112231].
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p01] More precisely, the general form is $[1^{\alpha _{1}}2^{\alpha _{2}}\dotsm n^{\alpha _{n}}]$ , where $\alpha _{1},\ldots ,\alpha _{n}$ are the numbers of cycles of respective length.
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p01] The number of cycle types of a set with n elements equals the value of the partition function $p(n)$ .
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p01] Polya's cycle index polynomial is a generating function which counts permutations by their cycle type.
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p01] In general, composing permutations written in cycle notation follows no easily described pattern – the cycles of the composition can be different from those being composed.
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p01] However the cycle type is preserved in the special case of conjugating a permutation $\sigma$ by another permutation $\pi$ , which means forming the product $\pi \sigma \pi ^{-1}$ .
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p01] Here, $\pi \sigma \pi ^{-1}$ is the *conjugate* of $\sigma$ by $\pi$ and its cycle notation can be obtained by taking the cycle notation for $\sigma$ and applying $\pi$ to all the entries in it.
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p01] It follows that two permutations are conjugate exactly when they have the same cycle type.
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p01] The order of a permutation $\sigma$ is the smallest positive integer *m* so that $\sigma ^{m}=\mathrm {id}$ .
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p01] It is the least common multiple of the lengths of its cycles.
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p01] Every permutation of a finite set can be expressed as the product of transpositions.
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p01] Although many such expressions for a given permutation may exist, either they all contain an even number of transpositions or they all contain an odd number of transpositions.
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p01] Thus all permutations can be classified as even or odd depending on this number.
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p01] This result can be extended so as to assign a *sign*, written $\operatorname {sgn} \sigma$ , to each permutation. $\operatorname {sgn} \sigma =+1$ if $\sigma$ is even and $\operatorname {sgn} \sigma =-1$ if $\sigma$ is odd.
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p01] The sign of a permutation is equal to the determinant of its permutation matrix (below).
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p01] A *permutation matrix* is an *n* × *n* matrix that has exactly one entry 1 in each column and in each row, and all other entries are 0.
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p01] There are several ways to assign a permutation matrix to a permutation of {1, 2, ..., *n*}.
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p01] One natural approach is to define $L_{\sigma }$ to be the linear transformation of $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ which permutes the standard basis $\{\mathbf {e} _{1},\ldots ,\mathbf {e} _{n}\}$ by $L_{\sigma }(\mathbf {e} _{j})=\mathbf {e} _{\sigma (j)}$ , and define $M_{\sigma }$ to be its matrix.
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p01] That is, $M_{\sigma }$ has its *j*th column equal to the n × 1 column vector $\mathbf {e} _{\sigma (j)}$ : its (*i*, *j*) entry is 1 if *i* = *σ*(*j*), and 0 otherwise.
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p01] It is also common in the literature to find the inverse convention, where a permutation *σ* is associated to the matrix $P_{\sigma }=(M_{\sigma })^{-1}=(M_{\sigma })^{T}$ whose (*i*, *j*) entry is 1 if *j* = *σ*(*i*) and is 0 otherwise.
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p01] In this convention, permutation matrices multiply in the opposite order from permutations, that is, $P_{\sigma }P_{\tau }=P_{\tau \sigma }$ .
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p01] The Cayley table on the right shows these matrices for permutations of 3 elements.
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p01] In some applications, the elements of the set being permuted will be compared with each other.
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p01] This requires that the set *S* has a total order so that any two elements can be compared.
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p01] The set {1, 2, ..., *n*} with the usual ≤ relation is the most frequently used set in these applications.
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p01] A number of properties of a permutation are directly related to the total ordering of *S,* considering the permutation written in one-line notation as a sequence $\sigma =\sigma (1)\sigma (2)\cdots \sigma (n)$ .
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p01] An *ascent* of a permutation *σ* of *n* is any position *i* < *n* where the following value is bigger than the current one.
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p01] For example, the permutation 3452167 has ascents (at positions) 1, 2, 5, and 6.
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p01] Similarly, a *descent* is a position *i* < *n* with $\sigma (i)>\sigma (i{+}1)$ , so every *i* with $1\leq i<n$ is either an ascent or a descent.
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p01] An *ascending run* of a permutation is a nonempty increasing contiguous subsequence that cannot be extended at either end; it corresponds to a maximal sequence of successive ascents (the latter may be empty: between two successive descents there is still an ascending run of length 1).
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p01] By contrast an *increasing subsequence* of a permutation is not necessarily contiguous: it is an increasing sequence obtained by omitting some of the values of the one-line notation.
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p01] For example, the permutation 2453167 has the ascending runs 245, 3, and 167, while it has an increasing subsequence 2367.
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p01] If a permutation has *k* − 1 descents, then it must be the union of *k* ascending runs.
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p01] The number of permutations of *n* with *k* ascents is (by definition) the Eulerian number $\textstyle \left\langle {n \atop k}\right\rangle$ ; this is also the number of permutations of *n* with *k* descents.
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p01] Some authors however define the Eulerian number $\textstyle \left\langle {n \atop k}\right\rangle$ as the number of permutations with *k* ascending runs, which corresponds to *k* − 1 descents.
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p01] An exceedance of a permutation *σ*1*σ*2...*σ**n* is an index *j* such that *σ**j* > *j*.
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p01] If the inequality is not strict (that is, *σ**j* ≥ *j*), then *j* is called a *weak exceedance*.
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p01] The number of *n*-permutations with *k* exceedances coincides with the number of *n*-permutations with *k* descents.
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p01] A *record* or *left-to-right maximum* of a permutation *σ* is an element *i* such that *σ*(*j*) < *σ*(*i*) for all *j < i*.
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p01] Foata's *fundamental bijection* transforms a permutation σ with a given canonical cycle form into the permutation $f(\sigma )={\hat {\sigma }}$ whose one-line notation has the same sequence of elements with parentheses removed.
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p01] Here the first element in each canonical cycle of σ becomes a record (left-to-right maximum) of ${\hat {\sigma }}$ .
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p01] Given ${\hat {\sigma }}$ , one may find its records and insert parentheses to construct the inverse transformation $\sigma =f^{-1}({\hat {\sigma }})$ .
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p01] Underlining the records in the above example: ${\hat {\sigma }}={\underline {5}}\,1\,3\,{\underline {6}}\,{\underline {8}}\,2\,7\,{\underline {9}}\,4$ , which allows the reconstruction of the cycles of σ.
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p01] The following table shows ${\hat {\sigma }}$ and σ for the six permutations of *S* = {1, 2, 3}, with the bold text on each side showing the notation used in the bijection: one-line notation for ${\hat {\sigma }}$ and canonical cycle notation for σ.
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p01] Furthermore, Foata's mapping takes an *n*-permutation with *k* weak exceedances to an *n*-permutation with *k* − 1 ascents.
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p01] An *inversion* of a permutation *σ* is a pair (*i*, *j*) of positions where the entries of a permutation are in the opposite order: $i<j$ and $\sigma (i)>\sigma (j)$ .
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p01] Thus a descent is an inversion at two adjacent positions.
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p01] Sometimes an inversion is defined as the pair of values (*σ*(*i*), *σ*(*j*)); this makes no difference for the *number* of inversions, and the reverse pair (*σ*(*j*), *σ*(*i*)) is an inversion in the above sense for the inverse permutation *σ*−1.
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p01] The number of inversions is an important measure for the degree to which the entries of a permutation are out of order; it is the same for *σ* and for *σ*−1.
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p01] To bring a permutation with *k* inversions into order (that is, transform it into the identity permutation), by successively applying (right-multiplication by) adjacent transpositions, is always possible and requires a sequence of *k* such operations.
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p01] This is so because applying such a transposition reduces the number of inversions by 1; as long as this number is not zero, the permutation is not the identity, so it has at least one descent.
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p01] Bubble sort and insertion sort can be interpreted as particular instances of this procedure to put a sequence into order.
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p01] Incidentally this procedure proves that any permutation *σ* can be written as a product of adjacent transpositions; for this one may simply reverse any sequence of such transpositions that transforms *σ* into the identity.
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p01] In fact, by enumerating all sequences of adjacent transpositions that would transform *σ* into the identity, one obtains (after reversal) a *complete* list of all expressions of minimal length writing *σ* as a product of adjacent transpositions.
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p01] The number of permutations of *n* with *k* inversions is expressed by a Mahonian number.
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p01] The notation $[n]_{q}!$ denotes the q-factorial.
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p01] This expansion commonly appears in the study of necklaces.
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p01] In this case, say the weight of the inversion $(i,j)$ is $\sigma (i)-\sigma (j)$ .
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p01] where $\leq$ denotes Bruhat order in the symmetric groups.
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p01] This graded partial order often appears in the context of Coxeter groups.
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p02] One way to represent permutations of *n* things is by an integer *N* with 0 ≤ *N* < *n*!, provided convenient methods are given to convert between the number and the representation of a permutation as an ordered arrangement (sequence).
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p02] This gives the most compact representation of arbitrary permutations, and in computing is particularly attractive when *n* is small enough that *N* can be held in a machine word; for 32-bit words this means *n* ≤ 12, and for 64-bit words this means *n* ≤ 20.
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p02] The conversion can be done via the intermediate form of a sequence of numbers *d**n*, *d**n*−1, ..., *d*2, *d*1, where *d**i* is a non-negative integer less than *i* (one may omit *d*1, as it is always 0, but its presence makes the subsequent conversion to a permutation easier to describe).
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p02] The first step then is to simply express *N* in the *factorial number system*, which is just a particular mixed radix representation, where, for numbers less than *n*!, the bases (place values or multiplication factors) for successive digits are (*n* − 1)!, (*n* − 2)!, ..., 2!, 1!.
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p02] The second step interprets this sequence as a Lehmer code or (almost equivalently) as an inversion table.
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p02] In the **Lehmer code** for a permutation *σ*, the number *d**n* represents the choice made for the first term *σ*1, the number *d**n*−1 represents the choice made for the second term *σ*2 among the remaining *n* − 1 elements of the set, and so forth.
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p02] More precisely, each *d**n*+1−*i* gives the number of *remaining* elements strictly less than the term *σ**i*.
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p02] Since those remaining elements are bound to turn up as some later term *σ**j*, the digit *d**n*+1−*i* counts the *inversions* (*i*,*j*) involving *i* as smaller index (the number of values *j* for which *i* < *j* and *σ**i* > *σ**j*).
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p02] The **inversion table** for *σ* is quite similar, but here *d**n*+1−*k* counts the number of inversions (*i*,*j*) where *k* = *σ**j* occurs as the smaller of the two values appearing in inverted order.
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p02] The Lehmer code lists the numbers of crosses in successive rows, while the inversion table lists the numbers of crosses in successive columns; it is just the Lehmer code for the inverse permutation, and vice versa.
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p02] Alternatively one could process the numbers from the inversion table and the elements of *S* both in the opposite order, starting with a row of *n* empty slots, and at each step place the element from *S* into the empty slot that is preceded by *d* other empty slots.
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p02] The sum of the numbers in the factorial number system representation gives the number of inversions of the permutation, and the parity of that sum gives the signature of the permutation.
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p02] In computing it may be required to generate permutations of a given sequence of values.
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p02] The methods best adapted to do this depend on whether one wants some randomly chosen permutations, or all permutations, and in the latter case if a specific ordering is required.
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p02] Another question is whether possible equality among entries in the given sequence is to be taken into account; if so, one should only generate distinct multiset permutations of the sequence.
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p02] An obvious way to generate permutations of *n* is to generate values for the Lehmer code (possibly using the factorial number system representation of integers up to *n*!), and convert those into the corresponding permutations.
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p02] With *n* likely to be rather small (especially if generation of all permutations is needed) that is not too much of a problem, but it turns out that both for random and for systematic generation there are simple alternatives that do considerably better.
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p02] For this reason it does not seem useful, although certainly possible, to employ a special data structure that would allow performing the conversion from Lehmer code to permutation in *O*(*n* log *n*) time.
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p02] For generating random permutations of a given sequence of *n* values, it makes no difference whether one applies a randomly selected permutation of *n* to the sequence, or chooses a random element from the set of distinct (multiset) permutations of the sequence.
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p02] This is because, even though in case of repeated values there can be many distinct permutations of *n* that result in the same permuted sequence, the number of such permutations is the same for each possible result.
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p02] Unlike for systematic generation, which becomes unfeasible for large *n* due to the growth of the number *n*!, there is no reason to assume that *n* will be small for random generation.
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p02] The basic idea to generate a random permutation is to generate at random one of the *n*! sequences of integers *d*1,*d*2,...,*d**n* satisfying 0 ≤ *d**i* < *i* (since *d*1 is always zero it may be omitted) and to convert it to a permutation through a bijective correspondence.
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p02] For the latter correspondence one could interpret the (reverse) sequence as a Lehmer code, and this gives a generation method first published in 1938 by Ronald Fisher and Frank Yates.
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p02] While at the time computer implementation was not an issue, this method suffers from the difficulty sketched above to convert from Lehmer code to permutation efficiently.
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p02] Thus the elements remaining for selection form a consecutive range at each point in time, even though they may not occur in the same order as they did in the original sequence.
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p02] The mapping from sequence of integers to permutations is somewhat complicated, but it can be seen to produce each permutation in exactly one way, by an immediate induction.
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p02] When the selected element happens to be the final remaining element, the swap operation can be omitted.
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p02] This does not occur sufficiently often to warrant testing for the condition, but the final element must be included among the candidates of the selection, to guarantee that all permutations can be generated.
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p02] If *d**i*+1 = *i*, the first assignment will copy an uninitialized value, but the second will overwrite it with the correct value *i*.
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p02] However, Fisher-Yates is not the fastest algorithm for generating a permutation, because Fisher-Yates is essentially a sequential algorithm and "divide and conquer" procedures can achieve the same result in parallel.
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p02] There are many ways to systematically generate all permutations of a given sequence.
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p02] One classic, simple, and flexible algorithm is based upon finding the next permutation in lexicographic ordering, if it exists.
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p02] It can handle repeated values, for which case it generates each distinct multiset permutation once.
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p02] Even for ordinary permutations it is significantly more efficient than generating values for the Lehmer code in lexicographic order (possibly using the factorial number system) and converting those to permutations.
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p02] It begins by sorting the sequence in (weakly) increasing order (which gives its lexicographically minimal permutation), and then repeats advancing to the next permutation as long as one is found.
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p02] The method goes back to Narayana Pandita in 14th century India, and has been rediscovered frequently.
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p02] The following algorithm generates the next permutation lexicographically after a given permutation.
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p02] It changes the given permutation in-place.
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p02] Find the largest index *l* greater than *k* such that *a*[*k*] < *a*[*l*].
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p02] Swap the value of *a*[*k*] with that of *a*[*l*].
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p02] Reverse the sequence from *a*[*k* + 1] up to and including the final element *a*[*n*].
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p02] Index *l* = 3, because 4 is the only value in the sequence that is greater than 3 in order to satisfy the condition *a*[*k*] < *a*[*l*].
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p02] The values of *a*[2] and *a*[3] are swapped to form the new sequence [1, 2, 4, 3].
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p02] The sequence after *k*-index *a*[2] to the final element is reversed.
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p02] Because only one value lies after this index (the 3), the sequence remains unchanged in this instance.
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p02] Thus the lexicographic successor of the initial state is permuted: [1, 2, 4, 3].
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p02] Following this algorithm, the next lexicographic permutation will be [1, 3, 2, 4], and the 24th permutation will be [4, 3, 2, 1] at which point *a*[*k*] < *a*[*k* + 1] does not exist, indicating that this is the last permutation.
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p02] This method uses about 3 comparisons and 1.5 swaps per permutation, amortized over the whole sequence, not counting the initial sort.
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p02] An alternative to the above algorithm, the Steinhaus–Johnson–Trotter algorithm, generates an ordering on all the permutations of a given sequence with the property that any two consecutive permutations in its output differ by swapping two adjacent values.
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p02] This ordering on the permutations was known to 17th-century English bell ringers, among whom it was known as "plain changes".
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p02] One advantage of this method is that the small amount of change from one permutation to the next allows the method to be implemented in constant time per permutation.
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p02] The same can also easily generate the subset of even permutations, again in constant time per permutation, by skipping every other output permutation.
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p02] An alternative to Steinhaus–Johnson–Trotter is Heap's algorithm, said by Robert Sedgewick in 1977 to be the fastest algorithm of generating permutations in applications.
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p02] The following figure shows the output of all three aforementioned algorithms for generating all permutations of length $n=4$ , and of six additional algorithms described in the literature.
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p02] Single-track Gray code: each column is a cyclic shift of the other columns, plus any two consecutive permutations differ only in one or two transpositions.
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p02] Nested swaps generating algorithm in steps connected to the nested subgroups $S_{k}\subset S_{k+1}$ .
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p02] Each permutation is obtained from the previous by a transposition multiplication to the left.
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p02] Algorithm is connected to the Factorial number system of the index.
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p02] Explicit sequence of swaps (transpositions, 2-cycles $(pq)$ ), is described here, each swap applied (on the left) to the previous chain providing a new permutation, such that all the permutations can be retrieved, each only once.
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p02] Since each $S_{m}$ is sequentially generated, there is a *last element* $\lambda _{m}\in S_{m}$ .
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p02] Then all swaps that generated $S_{k-1}$ are repeated, generating the whole coset $S_{k-1}\tau _{1}$ , reaching the last permutation in that coset $\lambda _{k-1}\tau _{1}$ ; the next swap has to move the permutation to representative of another coset $\tau _{2}=(p_{2}k)\lambda _{k-1}\tau _{1}$ .
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p02] Concluding, permutations $\tau _{i}\in S_{k}-S_{k-1}$ are all representatives of distinct cosets if and only if for any $k>j>i\geq 1$ , $(\lambda _{k-1})^{j-i}p_{i}\neq p_{j}$ (no repeat condition).
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p02] In particular, for all generated permutations to be distinct it is not necessary for the $p_{i}$ values to be distinct.
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p02] EXAMPLES: obviously, for $\lambda _{2}$ one has $\lambda _{2}=(12)$ ; to build $\lambda _{3}$ there are only two possibilities for the coset beginnings satisfying the no repeat condition; the choice $p_{1}=p_{2}=1$ leads to $\lambda _{3}=\lambda _{2}(13)\lambda _{2}(13)\lambda _{2}=(13)$ .
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p02] Then, to build $\lambda _{5}$ a convenient choice for the coset beginnings (satisfying the no repeat condition) is $p_{1}=p_{2}=p_{3}=p_{4}=1$ , leading to $\lambda _{5}=(15)$ .
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p02] From examples above one can inductively go to higher k in a similar way, choosing coset beginnings of $S_{k}$ in $S_{k+1}$ , as follows: for k even choosing all coset beginnings equal to 1 and for k odd choosing coset beginnings equal to $(1,2,\dots ,k)$ .
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p02] Using these explicit formulae one can easily compute the permutation of certain index in the counting/generation steps with minimum computation.
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p02] For this, writing the index in factorial base is useful.
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p02] Because multiplying by swap permutation takes short computing time and every new generated permutation requires only one such swap multiplication, this generation procedure is quite efficient.
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p02] Moreover, as there is a simple formula, having the last permutation in each $S_{k}$ can save even more time to go directly to a permutation with certain index in fewer steps than expected as it can be done in blocks of subgroups rather than swap by swap.
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p02] Permutations are used in the interleaver component of the error detection and correction algorithms, such as turbo codes, for example 3GPP Long Term Evolution mobile telecommunication standard uses these ideas (see 3GPP technical specification 36.212).
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p02] Such applications raise the question of fast generation of permutations satisfying certain desirable properties.
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p02] One of the methods is based on the permutation polynomials.
[src:discrete-mathematics/permutation-p02] Also as a base for optimal hashing in Unique Permutation Hashing.
[src:discrete-mathematics/pigeonhole-principle] In mathematics, the **pigeonhole principle** states that if n items are put into m containers, with *n* > *m*, then at least one container must contain more than one item.
[src:discrete-mathematics/pigeonhole-principle] For example, of three gloves, at least two must be right-handed or at least two must be left-handed, because there are three objects but only two categories of handedness to put them into.
[src:discrete-mathematics/pigeonhole-principle] This seemingly obvious statement, a type of counting argument, can be used to demonstrate possibly unexpected results.
[src:discrete-mathematics/pigeonhole-principle] For example, given that the population of London is more than one unit greater than the maximum number of hairs that can be on a human head, the principle requires that there must be at least two people in London who have the same number of hairs on their heads.
[src:discrete-mathematics/pigeonhole-principle] The principle has several generalizations and can be stated in various ways.
[src:discrete-mathematics/pigeonhole-principle] In a more quantified version: for natural numbers k and m, if *n* = *km* + 1 objects are distributed among m sets, the pigeonhole principle asserts that at least one of the sets will contain at least *k* + 1 objects.
[src:discrete-mathematics/pigeonhole-principle] For arbitrary n and m, this generalizes to $k+1=\lfloor (n-1)/m\rfloor +1=\lceil n/m\rceil$ , where $\lfloor \cdots \rfloor$ and $\lceil \cdots \rceil$ denote the floor and ceiling functions, respectively.
[src:discrete-mathematics/pigeonhole-principle] Though the principle's most straightforward application is to finite sets (such as pigeons and boxes), it is also used with infinite sets that cannot be put into one-to-one correspondence.
[src:discrete-mathematics/pigeonhole-principle] To do so requires the formal statement of the pigeonhole principle: "there does not exist an injective function whose codomain is smaller than its domain".
[src:discrete-mathematics/pigeonhole-principle] Advanced mathematical proofs like Siegel's lemma build upon this more general concept.
[src:discrete-mathematics/pigeonhole-principle] Dirichlet published his works in both French and German, using either the German *Schubfach* or the French *tiroir*.
[src:discrete-mathematics/pigeonhole-principle] The strict original meaning of these terms corresponds to the English *drawer*, that is, an *open-topped box that can be slid in and out of the cabinet that contains it*.
[src:discrete-mathematics/pigeonhole-principle] (Dirichlet wrote about distributing pearls among drawers.) These terms morphed to *pigeonhole* in the sense of a *small open space in a desk, cabinet, or wall for keeping letters or papers*, metaphorically rooted in structures that house pigeons.
[src:discrete-mathematics/pigeonhole-principle] Because furniture with pigeonholes is commonly used for storing or sorting things into many categories (such as letters in a post office or room keys in a hotel), the translation *pigeonhole* may be a better rendering of Dirichlet's original "drawer".
[src:discrete-mathematics/pigeonhole-principle] That understanding of the term *pigeonhole*, referring to some furniture features, is fading—especially among those who do not speak English natively but as a lingua franca in the scientific world—in favor of the more pictorial interpretation, literally involving pigeons and holes.
[src:discrete-mathematics/pigeonhole-principle] This suggestive (though not misleading) interpretation of "pigeonhole" as "dovecote" has lately found its way back to a German back-translation of the "pigeonhole principle" as the "*Taubenschlagprinzip*".
[src:discrete-mathematics/pigeonhole-principle] Suppose a drawer contains a mixture of black socks and blue socks, each of which can be worn on either foot.
[src:discrete-mathematics/pigeonhole-principle] You pull a number of socks from the drawer without looking.
[src:discrete-mathematics/pigeonhole-principle] What is the minimum number of pulled socks required to guarantee a pair of the same color?
[src:discrete-mathematics/pigeonhole-principle] By the pigeonhole principle (*m* = 2, using one pigeonhole per color), the answer is three (*n* = 3 items).
[src:discrete-mathematics/pigeonhole-principle] Either you have *three* of one color, or you have *two* of one color and *one* of the other.
[src:discrete-mathematics/pigeonhole-principle] If *n* people can shake hands with one another (where *n* > 1), the pigeonhole principle shows that there is always a pair of people who will shake hands with the same number of people.
[src:discrete-mathematics/pigeonhole-principle] In this application of the principle, the "hole" to which a person is assigned is the number of hands that person shakes.
[src:discrete-mathematics/pigeonhole-principle] Since each person shakes hands with some number of people from 0 to *n* − 1, there are *n* possible holes.
[src:discrete-mathematics/pigeonhole-principle] On the other hand, either the "0" hole, the "*n* − 1" hole, or both must be empty, for it is impossible (if *n* > 1) for some person to shake hands with everybody else while some person shakes hands with nobody.
[src:discrete-mathematics/pigeonhole-principle] This leaves *n* people to be placed into at most *n* − 1 non-empty holes, so the principle applies.
[src:discrete-mathematics/pigeonhole-principle] This hand-shaking example is equivalent to the statement that in any graph with more than one vertex, there is at least one pair of vertices that share the same degree.
[src:discrete-mathematics/pigeonhole-principle] This can be seen by associating each person with a vertex and each edge with a handshake.
[src:discrete-mathematics/pigeonhole-principle] One can demonstrate there must be at least two people in London with the same number of hairs on their heads as follows.
[src:discrete-mathematics/pigeonhole-principle] Since a typical human head has an average of around 150,000 hairs, it is reasonable to assume (as an upper bound) that no one has more than 1,000,000 hairs on their head (*m* = 1 million holes).
[src:discrete-mathematics/pigeonhole-principle] There are more than 1,000,000 people in London (*n* is bigger than 1 million items).
[src:discrete-mathematics/pigeonhole-principle] Assuming London has 9.002 million people, it follows that at least ten Londoners have the same number of hairs, as having nine Londoners in each of the 1 million pigeonholes accounts for only 9 million people.
[src:discrete-mathematics/pigeonhole-principle] For the average case (*m* = 150,000) with the constraint: fewest overlaps, there will be at most one person assigned to every pigeonhole and the 150,001st person assigned to the same pigeonhole as someone else.
[src:discrete-mathematics/pigeonhole-principle] In the absence of this constraint, there may be empty pigeonholes because the "collision" happens before the 150,001st person.
[src:discrete-mathematics/pigeonhole-principle] The principle just proves the existence of an overlap; it says nothing about the number of overlaps (which falls under the subject of probability distribution).
[src:discrete-mathematics/pigeonhole-principle] It seems that the question *whether there were any two persons in the World that have an equal number of hairs on their head?* had been raised in *The Athenian Mercury* before 1704.
[src:discrete-mathematics/pigeonhole-principle] The birthday problem asks, for a set of *n* randomly chosen people, what is the probability that some pair of them will have the same birthday?
[src:discrete-mathematics/pigeonhole-principle] The problem itself is mainly concerned with counterintuitive probabilities, but we can also tell by the pigeonhole principle that among 367 people, there is at least one pair of people who share the same birthday with 100% probability, as there are only 366 possible birthdays to choose from.
[src:discrete-mathematics/pigeonhole-principle] Imagine seven people who want to play in a tournament of teams (*n* = 7 items), with a limitation of only four teams (*m* = 4 holes) to choose from.
[src:discrete-mathematics/pigeonhole-principle] Any subset of size six from the set $S=\{1,2,3,\dots ,9\}$ must contain two elements whose sum is 10.
[src:discrete-mathematics/pigeonhole-principle] When the six "pigeons" (elements of the size six subset) are placed into these pigeonholes, each pigeon going into the pigeonhole that has it contained in its label, at least one of the pigeonholes labeled with a two-element subset will have two pigeons in it.
[src:discrete-mathematics/pigeonhole-principle] Hashing in computer science is the process of mapping an arbitrarily large set of data *n* to *m* fixed-size values.
[src:discrete-mathematics/pigeonhole-principle] This has applications in caching whereby large data sets can be stored by a reference to their representative values (their "hashes") in a "hash table" for fast recall.
[src:discrete-mathematics/pigeonhole-principle] The principle can be used to prove that any lossless compression algorithm, provided it makes some inputs smaller (as "compression" suggests), will also make some other inputs larger.
[src:discrete-mathematics/pigeonhole-principle] Otherwise, the set of all input sequences up to a given length L could be mapped to the (much) smaller set of all sequences of length less than L without collisions (because the compression is lossless), a possibility that the pigeonhole principle excludes.
[src:discrete-mathematics/pigeonhole-principle] A notable problem in mathematical analysis is, for a fixed irrational number a , to show that the set ⁠ $\{[na]:n\in \mathbb {Z} \}$ ⁠ of fractional parts is dense in $[0,1]$ .
[src:discrete-mathematics/pigeonhole-principle] One finds that it is not easy to explicitly find integers n , m such that $|na-m|<\varepsilon ,$ where $\varepsilon >0$ is a small positive number and a is some arbitrary irrational number.
[src:discrete-mathematics/pigeonhole-principle] But if one takes M such that $1/M<\varepsilon$ , by the pigeonhole principle there must be $n_{1},n_{2}\in \{1,2,\ldots ,M+1\}$ such that $n_{1}a$ and $n_{2}a$ are in the same integer subdivision of size $1/M$ (there are only M such subdivisions between consecutive integers).
[src:discrete-mathematics/pigeonhole-principle] This shows that 0 is a limit point of $\{[na]\}$ .
[src:discrete-mathematics/pigeonhole-principle] One can then use this fact to prove the case for p in $(0,1]$ : find n such that $[na]<1/M<\varepsilon$ ; then if $p\in (0,1/M]$ , the proof is complete.
[src:discrete-mathematics/pigeonhole-principle] In the proof of the pumping lemma for regular languages, a version that mixes finite and infinite sets is used: If infinitely many objects are placed into finitely many boxes, then two objects share a box.
[src:discrete-mathematics/pigeonhole-principle] In Fisk's solution to the Art gallery problem a sort of converse is used: If n objects are placed into k boxes, then there is a box containing at most $n/k$ objects.
[src:discrete-mathematics/pigeonhole-principle] The following are alternative formulations of the pigeonhole principle.
[src:discrete-mathematics/pigeonhole-principle] (equivalent formulation of 1) If *n* objects are distributed over *n* places in such a way that no place receives more than one object, then each place receives exactly one object.
[src:discrete-mathematics/pigeonhole-principle] (generalization of 1) If *S* and *T* are sets, and the cardinality of *S* is greater than the cardinality of *T*, then there is no injective function from *S* to *T*.
[src:discrete-mathematics/pigeonhole-principle] If *n* objects are distributed over *m* places, and if *n* < *m*, then some place receives no object.
[src:discrete-mathematics/pigeonhole-principle] (equivalent formulation of 4) If *n* objects are distributed over *n* places in such a way that no place receives no object, then each place receives exactly one object.
[src:discrete-mathematics/pigeonhole-principle] (generalization of 4) If *S* and *T* are sets, and the cardinality of *S* is less than the cardinality of *T*, then there is no surjective function from *S* to *T*.
[src:discrete-mathematics/pigeonhole-principle] objects are distributed into *n* boxes, then either the first box contains at least *q*1 objects, or the second box contains at least *q*2 objects, ..., or the *n*th box contains at least *q**n* objects.
[src:discrete-mathematics/pigeonhole-principle] The simple form is obtained from this by taking *q*1 = *q*2 = ... = *q**n* = 2, which gives *n* + 1 objects.
[src:discrete-mathematics/pigeonhole-principle] If *n*(*r* − 1) + 1 objects are distributed into *n* boxes, then at least one of the boxes contains *r* or more of the objects.
[src:discrete-mathematics/pigeonhole-principle] This can also be stated as, if *k* discrete objects are to be allocated to *n* containers, then at least one container must hold at least $\lceil k/n\rceil$ objects, where $\lceil x\rceil$ is the ceiling function, denoting the smallest integer larger than or equal to *x*.
[src:discrete-mathematics/pigeonhole-principle] Similarly, at least one container must hold no more than $\lfloor k/n\rfloor$ objects, where $\lfloor x\rfloor$ is the floor function, denoting the largest integer smaller than or equal to *x*.
[src:discrete-mathematics/pigeonhole-principle] For *n* = 0 and for *n* = 1 (and *m* > 0), that probability is zero; in other words, if there is just one pigeon, there cannot be a conflict.
[src:discrete-mathematics/pigeonhole-principle] For *n* > *m* (more pigeons than pigeonholes) it is one, in which case it coincides with the ordinary pigeonhole principle.
[src:discrete-mathematics/pigeonhole-principle] But even if the number of pigeons does not exceed the number of pigeonholes (*n* ≤ *m*), due to the random nature of the assignment of pigeons to pigeonholes there is often a substantial chance that clashes will occur.
[src:discrete-mathematics/pigeonhole-principle] For example, if 2 pigeons are randomly assigned to 4 pigeonholes, there is a 25% chance that at least one pigeonhole will hold more than one pigeon; for 5 pigeons and 10 holes, that probability is 69.76%; and for 10 pigeons and 20 holes it is about 93.45%.
[src:discrete-mathematics/pigeonhole-principle] If the number of holes stays fixed, there is always a greater probability of a pair when you add more pigeons.
[src:discrete-mathematics/pigeonhole-principle] This problem is treated at much greater length in the birthday paradox.
[src:discrete-mathematics/pigeonhole-principle] A further probabilistic generalization is that when a real-valued random variable *X* has a finite mean *E*(*X*), then the probability is nonzero that *X* is greater than or equal to *E*(*X*), and similarly the probability is nonzero that *X* is less than or equal to *E*(*X*).
[src:discrete-mathematics/pigeonhole-principle] To see that this implies the standard pigeonhole principle, take any fixed arrangement of *n* pigeons into *m* holes and let *X* be the number of pigeons in a hole chosen uniformly at random.
[src:discrete-mathematics/pigeonhole-principle] The mean of *X* is *n*/*m*, so if there are more pigeons than holes the mean is greater than one.
[src:discrete-mathematics/pigeonhole-principle] The pigeonhole principle can be extended to infinite sets by phrasing it in terms of cardinal numbers: if the cardinality of set A is greater than the cardinality of set B, then there is no injection from A to B.
[src:discrete-mathematics/pigeonhole-principle] However, in this form the principle is tautological, since the meaning of the statement that the cardinality of set A is greater than the cardinality of set B is exactly that there is no injective map from A to B.
[src:discrete-mathematics/pigeonhole-principle] However, adding at least one element to a finite set is sufficient to ensure that the cardinality increases.
[src:discrete-mathematics/pigeonhole-principle] Another way to phrase the pigeonhole principle for finite sets is similar to the principle that finite sets are Dedekind finite: Let A and B be finite sets.
[src:discrete-mathematics/pigeonhole-principle] If there is a surjection from A to B that is not injective, then no surjection from A to B is injective.
[src:discrete-mathematics/pigeonhole-principle] In fact no function of any kind from A to B is injective.
[src:discrete-mathematics/pigeonhole-principle] This is not true for infinite sets: Consider the function on the natural numbers that sends 1 and 2 to 1, 3 and 4 to 2, 5 and 6 to 3, and so on.
[src:discrete-mathematics/pigeonhole-principle] There is a similar principle for infinite sets: If uncountably many pigeons are stuffed into countably many pigeonholes, there will exist at least one pigeonhole having uncountably many pigeons stuffed into it.
[src:discrete-mathematics/pigeonhole-principle] This principle is not a generalization of the pigeonhole principle for finite sets however: It is in general false for finite sets.
[src:discrete-mathematics/pigeonhole-principle] In technical terms it says that if A and B are finite sets such that any surjective function from A to B is not injective, then there exists an element b of B such that there exists a bijection between the preimage of b and A.
[src:discrete-mathematics/pigeonhole-principle] This is a quite different statement, and is absurd for large finite cardinalities.
[src:discrete-mathematics/pigeonhole-principle] Yakir Aharonov et al. presented arguments that quantum mechanics may violate the pigeonhole principle, and proposed interferometric experiments to test the pigeonhole principle in quantum mechanics.
[src:discrete-mathematics/pigeonhole-principle] Later research has called this conclusion into question.
[src:discrete-mathematics/pigeonhole-principle] In a January 2015 arXiv preprint, researchers Alastair Rae and Ted Forgan at the University of Birmingham performed a theoretical wave function analysis, employing the standard pigeonhole principle, on the flight of electrons at various energies through an interferometer.
[src:discrete-mathematics/pigeonhole-principle] If the electrons had no interaction strength at all, they would each produce a single, perfectly circular peak.
[src:discrete-mathematics/pigeonhole-principle] If the interaction strength was fairly low, as would be the case in many real experiments, the deviation from a zero-interaction pattern would be nearly indiscernible, much smaller than the lattice spacing of atoms in solids, such as the detectors used for observing these patterns.
[src:discrete-mathematics/pigeonhole-principle] This would make it very difficult or impossible to distinguish a weak-but-nonzero interaction strength from no interaction whatsoever, and thus give an illusion of three electrons that did not interact despite all three passing through two paths.
[src:discrete-mathematics/recurrence-relation] In mathematics and computer science, a **recurrence relation** is an equation according to which the n th term of a sequence of numbers is equal to some combination of the previous terms.
[src:discrete-mathematics/recurrence-relation] Often, only k previous terms of the sequence appear in the equation, for a parameter k that is independent of n ; this number k is called the *order* of the relation.
[src:discrete-mathematics/recurrence-relation] If the values of the first k numbers in the sequence have been given, the rest of the sequence can be calculated by repeatedly applying the equation.
[src:discrete-mathematics/recurrence-relation] In *linear recurrences*, the nth term is equated to a linear function of the k previous terms.
[src:discrete-mathematics/recurrence-relation] A famous example is the recurrence for the Fibonacci numbers, $F_{n}=F_{n-1}+F_{n-2}$ where the order k is two and the linear function merely adds the two previous terms.
[src:discrete-mathematics/recurrence-relation] This example is a linear recurrence with constant coefficients, because the coefficients of the linear function (1 and 1) are constants that do not depend on $n.$ For these recurrences, one can express the general term of the sequence as a closed-form expression of n .
[src:discrete-mathematics/recurrence-relation] As well, linear recurrences with polynomial coefficients depending on n are also important, because many common elementary functions and special functions have a Taylor series whose coefficients satisfy such a recurrence relation (see holonomic function).
[src:discrete-mathematics/recurrence-relation] Solving a recurrence relation means obtaining a closed-form solution: a non-recursive function of n .
[src:discrete-mathematics/recurrence-relation] The concept of a recurrence relation can be extended to multidimensional arrays, that is, indexed families that are indexed by tuples of natural numbers.
[src:discrete-mathematics/recurrence-relation] A *recurrence relation* is an equation that expresses each element of a sequence as a function of the preceding ones.
[src:discrete-mathematics/recurrence-relation] is a function, where X is a set to which the elements of a sequence must belong.
[src:discrete-mathematics/recurrence-relation] For any $u_{0}\in X$ , this defines a unique sequence with $u_{0}$ as its first element, called the *initial value*.
[src:discrete-mathematics/recurrence-relation] It is easy to modify the definition for getting sequences starting from the term of index 1 or higher.
[src:discrete-mathematics/recurrence-relation] This defines recurrence relation of *first order*.
[src:discrete-mathematics/recurrence-relation] where $\varphi :\mathbb {N} \times X^{k}\to X$ is a function that involves k consecutive elements of the sequence.
[src:discrete-mathematics/recurrence-relation] In this case, k initial values are needed for defining a sequence.
[src:discrete-mathematics/recurrence-relation] for a given constant $r.$ The behavior of the sequence depends dramatically on $r,$ but is stable when the initial condition $x_{0}$ varies.
[src:discrete-mathematics/recurrence-relation] The recurrence of order two satisfied by the Fibonacci numbers is the canonical example of a homogeneous linear recurrence relation with constant coefficients (see below).
[src:discrete-mathematics/recurrence-relation] A simple example of a multidimensional recurrence relation is given by the binomial coefficients ${\tbinom {n}{k}}$ , which count the ways of selecting k elements out of a set of n elements.
[src:discrete-mathematics/recurrence-relation] Using this formula to compute the values of all binomial coefficients generates an infinite array called Pascal's triangle.
[src:discrete-mathematics/recurrence-relation] with the initial value ${\textstyle {\binom {n}{0}}=1}$ (The division is not displayed as a fraction for emphasizing that it must be computed after the multiplication, for not introducing fractional numbers).
[src:discrete-mathematics/recurrence-relation] The **difference operator** is an operator that maps sequences to sequences, and, more generally, functions to functions.
[src:discrete-mathematics/recurrence-relation] It is thus a special case of finite difference.
[src:discrete-mathematics/recurrence-relation] A **difference equation** of order k is an equation that involves the k first differences of a sequence or a function, in the same way as a differential equation of order k relates the k first derivatives of a function.
[src:discrete-mathematics/recurrence-relation] The two above relations allow transforming a recurrence relation of order k into a difference equation of order k, and, conversely, a difference equation of order k into recurrence relation of order k.
[src:discrete-mathematics/recurrence-relation] Each transformation is the inverse of the other, and the sequences that are solution of the difference equation are exactly those that satisfies the recurrence relation.
[src:discrete-mathematics/recurrence-relation] in the sense that the two equations are satisfied by the same sequences.
[src:discrete-mathematics/recurrence-relation] See Rational difference equation, Linear constant-coefficient difference equation and Matrix difference equation for examples of using "difference equation" instead of "recurrence relation".
[src:discrete-mathematics/recurrence-relation] Difference equations resemble differential equations, and this resemblance is often used to mimic methods for solving differentiable equations to apply to solving difference equations, and therefore recurrence relations.
[src:discrete-mathematics/recurrence-relation] Summation equations relate to difference equations as integral equations relate to differential equations.
[src:discrete-mathematics/recurrence-relation] See time scale calculus for a unification of the theory of difference equations with that of differential equations.
[src:discrete-mathematics/recurrence-relation] Single-variable or one-dimensional recurrence relations are about sequences (i.e. functions defined on one-dimensional grids).
[src:discrete-mathematics/recurrence-relation] Multi-variable or n-dimensional recurrence relations are about n -dimensional grids.
[src:discrete-mathematics/recurrence-relation] Functions defined on n -grids can also be studied with partial difference equations.
[src:discrete-mathematics/recurrence-relation] If we apply the formula to $a_{n+1}=(1+hf_{nh})a_{n}+hg_{nh}$ and take the limit $h\to 0$ , we get the formula for first order linear differential equations with variable coefficients; the sum becomes an integral, and the product becomes the exponential function of an integral.
[src:discrete-mathematics/recurrence-relation] Many homogeneous linear recurrence relations may be solved by means of the generalized hypergeometric series.
[src:discrete-mathematics/recurrence-relation] Special cases of these lead to recurrence relations for the orthogonal polynomials, and many special functions.
[src:discrete-mathematics/recurrence-relation] Sequences which are the solutions of linear difference equations with polynomial coefficients are called P-recursive.
[src:discrete-mathematics/recurrence-relation] For these specific recurrence equations algorithms are known which find polynomial, rational or hypergeometric solutions.
[src:discrete-mathematics/recurrence-relation] Furthermore, for the general non-homogeneous linear recurrence relation with constant coefficients, one can solve it based on variation of parameter.
[src:discrete-mathematics/recurrence-relation] A first order rational difference equation has the form $w_{t+1}={\tfrac {aw_{t}+b}{cw_{t}+d}}$ .
[src:discrete-mathematics/recurrence-relation] Such an equation can be solved by writing $w_{t}$ as a nonlinear transformation of another variable $x_{t}$ which itself evolves linearly.
[src:discrete-mathematics/recurrence-relation] Then standard methods can be used to solve the linear difference equation in $x_{t}$ .
[src:discrete-mathematics/recurrence-relation] The recurrence is stable, meaning that the iterates converge asymptotically to a fixed value, if and only if the eigenvalues (i.e., the roots of the characteristic equation), whether real or complex, are all less than unity in absolute value.
[src:discrete-mathematics/recurrence-relation] with state vector x and transition matrix A , x converges asymptotically to the steady state vector $x^{*}$ if and only if all eigenvalues of the transition matrix A (whether real or complex) have an absolute value which is less than 1.
[src:discrete-mathematics/recurrence-relation] A nonlinear recurrence could have multiple fixed points, in which case some fixed points may be locally stable and others locally unstable; for continuous *f* two adjacent fixed points cannot both be locally stable.
[src:discrete-mathematics/recurrence-relation] A nonlinear recurrence relation could also have a cycle of period k for $k>1$ .
[src:discrete-mathematics/recurrence-relation] where $x^{*}$ is any point on the cycle.
[src:discrete-mathematics/recurrence-relation] In a chaotic recurrence relation, the variable x stays in a bounded region but never converges to a fixed point or an attracting cycle; any fixed points or cycles of the equation are unstable.
[src:discrete-mathematics/recurrence-relation] See also logistic map, dyadic transformation, and tent map.
[src:discrete-mathematics/recurrence-relation] When solving an ordinary differential equation numerically, one typically encounters a recurrence relation.
[src:discrete-mathematics/recurrence-relation] Systems of linear first order differential equations can be discretized exactly analytically using the methods shown in the discretization article.
[src:discrete-mathematics/recurrence-relation] Some of the best-known difference equations have their origins in the attempt to model population dynamics.
[src:discrete-mathematics/recurrence-relation] For example, the Fibonacci numbers were once used as a model for the growth of a rabbit population.
[src:discrete-mathematics/recurrence-relation] The logistic map is used either directly to model population growth, or as a starting point for more detailed models of population dynamics.
[src:discrete-mathematics/recurrence-relation] In this context, coupled difference equations are often used to model the interaction of two or more populations.
[src:discrete-mathematics/recurrence-relation] with $N_{t}$ representing the hosts, and $P_{t}$ the parasites, at time t .
[src:discrete-mathematics/recurrence-relation] Integrodifference equations are a form of recurrence relation important to spatial ecology.
[src:discrete-mathematics/recurrence-relation] These and other difference equations are particularly suited to modeling univoltine populations.
[src:discrete-mathematics/recurrence-relation] Recurrence relations are also of fundamental importance in analysis of algorithms.
[src:discrete-mathematics/recurrence-relation] If an algorithm is designed so that it will break a problem into smaller subproblems (divide and conquer), its running time is described by a recurrence relation.
[src:discrete-mathematics/recurrence-relation] A simple example is the time an algorithm takes to find an element in an ordered vector with n elements, in the worst case.
[src:discrete-mathematics/recurrence-relation] A naive algorithm will search from left to right, one element at a time.
[src:discrete-mathematics/recurrence-relation] The worst possible scenario is when the required element is the last, so the number of comparisons is n .
[src:discrete-mathematics/recurrence-relation] A better algorithm is called binary search.
[src:discrete-mathematics/recurrence-relation] It will first check if the element is at the middle of the vector.
[src:discrete-mathematics/recurrence-relation] If not, then it will check if the middle element is greater or lesser than the sought element.
[src:discrete-mathematics/recurrence-relation] At this point, half of the vector can be discarded, and the algorithm can be run again on the other half.
[src:discrete-mathematics/recurrence-relation] the time complexity of which will be $O(\log _{2}(n))$ .
[src:discrete-mathematics/recurrence-relation] In digital signal processing, recurrence relations can model feedback in a system, where outputs at one time become inputs for future time.
[src:discrete-mathematics/recurrence-relation] They thus arise in infinite impulse response (IIR) digital filters.
[src:discrete-mathematics/recurrence-relation] where $x_{t}$ is the input at time t , $y_{t}$ is the output at time t , and $\alpha$ controls how much of the delayed signal is fed back into the output.
[src:discrete-mathematics/recurrence-relation] Recurrence relations, especially linear recurrence relations, are used extensively in both theoretical and empirical economics.
[src:discrete-mathematics/recurrence-relation] In particular, in macroeconomics one might develop a model of various broad sectors of the economy (the financial sector, the goods sector, the labor market, etc.) in which some agents' actions depend on lagged variables.
[src:discrete-mathematics/recurrence-relation] The model would then be solved for current values of key variables (interest rate, real GDP, etc.) in terms of past and current values of other variables.
[src:discrete-mathematics/set-theory] The modern study of set theory was initiated by the German mathematicians Richard Dedekind and Georg Cantor in the 1870s.
[src:discrete-mathematics/set-theory] In particular, Georg Cantor is commonly considered the founder of set theory.
[src:discrete-mathematics/set-theory] The non-formalized systems investigated during this early stage go under the name of *naive set theory*.
[src:discrete-mathematics/set-theory] After the discovery of paradoxes within naive set theory (e.g.
[src:discrete-mathematics/set-theory] Russell's paradox, Cantor's paradox, and the Burali-Forti paradox, et al.), various axiomatic systems were proposed in the early twentieth century, of which Zermelo–Fraenkel set theory (with or without the axiom of choice) is still the best-known and most studied.
[src:discrete-mathematics/set-theory] Set theory is commonly employed as a foundational system for the whole of mathematics, particularly in the form of Zermelo–Fraenkel set theory with the axiom of choice.
[src:discrete-mathematics/set-theory] Besides its foundational role, set theory also provides the framework to develop a mathematical theory of infinity, and has various applications in computer science (such as in the theory of relational algebra), philosophy, formal semantics, and evolutionary dynamics.
[src:discrete-mathematics/set-theory] Its foundational appeal, together with its paradoxes, and its implications for the concept of infinity and its multiple applications have made set theory an area of major interest for logicians and philosophers of mathematics.
[src:discrete-mathematics/set-theory] Contemporary research into set theory covers a vast array of topics, ranging from the structure of the real number line to the study of the consistency of large cardinals.
[src:discrete-mathematics/set-theory] The basic notion of grouping objects has existed since at least the emergence of numbers, and the notion of treating sets as their own objects has existed since at least the Tree of Porphyry in 3rd-century CE.
[src:discrete-mathematics/set-theory] The simplicity and ubiquity of sets makes it hard to determine the origin of sets as now used in mathematics; however, Bernard Bolzano's *Paradoxes of the Infinite* (*Paradoxien des Unendlichen*, 1851) is generally considered the first rigorous introduction of sets to mathematics.
[src:discrete-mathematics/set-theory] In his work, he (among other things) expanded on Galileo's paradox, and introduced one-to-one correspondence of infinite sets, for example between the intervals $[0,5]$ and $[0,12]$ by the relation $5y=12x$ .
[src:discrete-mathematics/set-theory] However, he resisted saying these sets were equinumerous, and his work is generally considered to have been uninfluential in mathematics of his time.
[src:discrete-mathematics/set-theory] Before mathematical set theory, basic concepts of infinity were considered to be in the domain of philosophy (see: *Infinity (philosophy)* and *Infinity § History*).
[src:discrete-mathematics/set-theory] Since the 5th century BC, beginning with Greek philosopher Zeno of Elea in the West (and early Indian mathematicians in the East), mathematicians had struggled with the concept of infinity.
